1
00:00:04,480 --> 00:00:05,120
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:06,080 --> 00:00:07,440
New York in the spring

3
00:00:12,080 --> 00:00:18,720
It was a fine but chilly spring morning. Fine 
enough even to make the New York borough of Queens  

4
00:00:18,720 --> 00:00:25,440
seem attractive. Like any other day, I 
left my apartment on Main Street, Queens,  

5
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:31,120
and walked to the subway station to commute into 
midtown Manhattan on the number seven train.  

6
00:00:32,480 --> 00:00:37,680
Like any other day, I read the New York 
Daily News to pass the time during the  

7
00:00:37,680 --> 00:00:44,640
journey. Out of professional interest, I always 
glance through the day's fresh crime stories.  

8
00:00:45,680 --> 00:00:52,400
Muggings, thefts, a car-jacking, a 
shooting, a bank robbery, and so on.  

9
00:00:53,440 --> 00:00:58,800
Crime - the unpleasant reality of 
life from which I make my living.

10
00:01:00,160 --> 00:01:05,280
The name's Marley, Nat Marley, 
licensed private investigator.  

11
00:01:06,480 --> 00:01:14,000
My prediction is that you already have a mental 
image of my type of work. I can safely bet that  

12
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:20,640
your image comes straight from the fantasy world 
of Hollywood. That's a long way from the truth.  

13
00:01:21,840 --> 00:01:28,560
The majority of my work is dull. Often 
just pure routine stuff like divorce,  

14
00:01:29,120 --> 00:01:35,840
bad debts, or missing persons. Don't imagine 
for a moment that I'm good-looking either.  

15
00:01:36,800 --> 00:01:43,360
Just an ordinary-looking guy, bald, 
overweight and on the wrong side of forty.  

16
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:50,240
And let's get another thing straight, my 
working days seldom start with a wealthy,  

17
00:01:50,240 --> 00:01:55,120
attractive female client anxiously 
waiting for my professional services.

18
00:01:56,960 --> 00:02:02,880
My office is on East 43rd Street, just a 
couple of blocks from Grand Central Station.  

19
00:02:04,480 --> 00:02:10,400
Stella Delgado, my personal assistant was 
already at her desk talking on the phone.

20
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:18,240
Stella's been with me most of the time I've been 
in business. A beautiful, intelligent Puerto Rican  

21
00:02:18,240 --> 00:02:26,080
in her late twenties. If she wanted, she could 
get a far better job elsewhere. And I've told  

22
00:02:26,080 --> 00:02:34,720
her that too. But she insists on working for me; 
she must like me. You've heard of the expression  

23
00:02:34,720 --> 00:02:40,640
'on the wrong side of the tracks', meaning the 
poor, underprivileged areas of the inner city?  

24
00:02:41,840 --> 00:02:46,240
That's where Stella grew up, in 
the Barrio on the Upper East Side,  

25
00:02:46,880 --> 00:02:53,840
known as Spanish Harlem. She had left school 
early and got into plenty of trouble as a kid.  

26
00:02:55,040 --> 00:02:59,600
Then it took years of night school 
study to catch up on her education.

27
00:03:01,280 --> 00:03:06,480
As she put down the phone, I asked, "How are 
things on this beautiful spring morning?"

28
00:03:07,920 --> 00:03:15,680
Silence. She just gave me a blank stare. 
The morning mail was on her desk, unopened.  

29
00:03:16,800 --> 00:03:23,600
Something was definitely wrong. "Stella, 
what's the matter? Come on, out with it."

30
00:03:25,040 --> 00:03:33,760
She looked up at me tearfully. "Nat, I don't know 
what to do. It's family - my kid brother, Jose.  

31
00:03:34,800 --> 00:03:41,280
I've just been talking to him on the phone. He's 
been arrested. He could be in serious trouble."

32
00:03:42,960 --> 00:03:49,680
There was work to catch up with that morning, 
bills to send out to our satisfied or dissatisfied  

33
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:56,960
clients, and some annoying letters from 
the IRS, the tax people. Yet again,  

34
00:03:56,960 --> 00:04:03,840
they'd claimed I hadn't paid enough tax. 
But clients and the IRS would have to wait.

35
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:06,640
"Stella, tell me everything."

36
00:04:07,840 --> 00:04:15,920
"It's a long story. Jose was found by the police 
in the early hours of this morning on 112th Street  

37
00:04:15,920 --> 00:04:23,120
just off Lexington Avenue, Upper East Side. 
He was lying unconscious with head injuries,  

38
00:04:23,120 --> 00:04:30,160
in the driver's seat of a car that had 
crashed into a wall in a parking lot. Nat,  

39
00:04:30,720 --> 00:04:38,880
he doesn't even own a car. Anyway, he was taken to 
the emergency room at Metropolitan Hospital. Now  

40
00:04:38,880 --> 00:04:46,400
he's in a secure room under police guard. He was 
allowed to make one phone call, so he called me."

41
00:04:47,840 --> 00:04:52,160
"So what's the story? How did 
he get into this mess?" I asked.

42
00:04:53,280 --> 00:05:00,800
"The awful thing is he has no memory of what he 
was doing," Stella said. "All he can remember  

43
00:05:00,800 --> 00:05:07,600
is being at some bar in Brighton Beach with 
his buddies yesterday evening. Then nothing."

44
00:05:08,960 --> 00:05:11,520
"Has he been charged with anything?" I asked.

45
00:05:12,320 --> 00:05:17,040
"No. At least, not as far 
as I know," replied Stella.

46
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:22,720
"Why were Jose and his buddies going out 
for a drink at Brighton Beach, anyway?  

47
00:05:23,520 --> 00:05:26,480
That's quite a way from Spanish 
Harlem for a night out."

48
00:05:27,760 --> 00:05:34,400
"Jose works in the summer at a diner on Surf 
Avenue, Coney Island. The place closes up  

49
00:05:34,400 --> 00:05:40,480
in the winter. Jose had been to see his 
boss to confirm his job for next summer.  

50
00:05:41,360 --> 00:05:47,760
He got some good news - they took him on 
as a cook. Jose had taken a couple of his  

51
00:05:47,760 --> 00:05:56,000
buddies along to see if he could fix up work for 
them. They were taken on as waiters. Good money,  

52
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:02,240
plus room and board, starting first of April. 
Afterwards, they went out to celebrate."

53
00:06:03,680 --> 00:06:08,480
The thought of Coney Island brought back 
some of those golden childhood memories:  

54
00:06:09,360 --> 00:06:16,480
trips to Coney Island beach and the rides at the 
amusement park, family vacations at the beach.  

55
00:06:17,760 --> 00:06:23,360
I put those thoughts to the back of my 
mind and concentrated on Stella's story.

56
00:06:24,800 --> 00:06:26,320
"Anything more?" I asked.

57
00:06:27,360 --> 00:06:34,240
"He said he had just a vague memory of a 
bar somewhere on Brighton Beach Avenue.  

58
00:06:34,240 --> 00:06:41,120
He knew he'd had a few too many drinks. Then 
nothing until he woke up in a hospital bed."

59
00:06:42,320 --> 00:06:50,000
"Maybe he's in shock," I suggested. "Temporary 
memory loss. If this was a simple case of  

60
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:56,080
drunk-driving, he wouldn't be under police 
guard. And where did he get the car from?"

61
00:06:57,120 --> 00:07:01,840
"I don't know, Nat. Jose's 
never had a driver's license."

62
00:07:02,880 --> 00:07:06,960
Not having a driver's license 
didn't mean he hadn't stolen the car  

63
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:10,880
and driven it anyway. But I 
didn't say that to Stella.

64
00:07:12,240 --> 00:07:16,960
I thought for a moment. If Jose 
hadn't been charged with any offense,  

65
00:07:17,600 --> 00:07:21,040
the NYPD could only hold him for a limited time.

66
00:07:22,320 --> 00:07:29,680
"All right, Stella. This is what we'll do. If Jose 
hasn't been formally charged, there's no reason  

67
00:07:29,680 --> 00:07:35,680
why we shouldn't be allowed to visit. We're going 
straight over to the hospital to talk with him."

68
00:07:37,120 --> 00:07:41,920
Stella didn't move but just stood 
by her desk, biting her lip.

69
00:07:43,040 --> 00:07:45,520
"Is something else bothering you?" I asked.

70
00:07:46,640 --> 00:07:53,520
"Nat, I'm worried sick. Jose's an ordinary 
loveable guy who likes a good time.  

71
00:07:54,400 --> 00:07:59,840
OK, he's got a criminal record. He got 
into some trouble when he was a teenager.  

72
00:08:00,720 --> 00:08:07,120
But I know he's harmless. A danger to 
nobody. But someone with his background...  

73
00:08:08,240 --> 00:08:12,160
you know as well as I do what 
conclusion the police will come to."

74
00:08:13,440 --> 00:08:20,480
"Come on, Stella," I said. "Things have changed 
in this city. It's not like the bad old days.  

75
00:08:21,280 --> 00:08:26,960
You know how sensitive the police are nowadays 
about any question of possible prejudice.  

76
00:08:27,840 --> 00:08:32,160
You can't assume that the 
NYPD will think Jose is guilty  

77
00:08:32,160 --> 00:08:37,120
because of his background. Any suspect 
has to be judged on the evidence."

78
00:08:38,560 --> 00:08:41,280
"Maybe you're right," she replied, simply.

79
00:08:42,720 --> 00:08:49,040
Stella didn't seem to be convinced. But 
I knew the NYPD would go to any lengths  

80
00:08:49,040 --> 00:08:54,160
to avoid the kind of publicity an accusation 
of racial prejudice would attract.  

81
00:08:55,440 --> 00:09:04,560
I also understood Stella's fears. Stella and her 
family are Puerto Rican. During the 1950s tens  

82
00:09:04,560 --> 00:09:11,120
of thousands of Puerto Ricans emigrated from 
their island to the U.S.A. When they arrived,  

83
00:09:11,680 --> 00:09:16,800
some of them discovered that the U.S.A. wasn't 
the land of opportunity they'd expected.  

84
00:09:17,840 --> 00:09:22,960
Some had exchanged the poverty of Puerto 
Rico for the poor neighborhoods of New York.  

85
00:09:24,160 --> 00:09:30,000
There were dead-end jobs waiting for them as 
kitchen hands or unskilled factory workers.  

86
00:09:31,360 --> 00:09:36,960
Today, however, some have succeeded 
in creating a good life - like Stella,  

87
00:09:36,960 --> 00:09:44,560
with a permanent job, comfortable apartment, 
and loving husband. But for Stella it had been  

88
00:09:44,560 --> 00:09:51,280
a struggle. I could appreciate how her culture and 
background might affect the way she saw things.

89
00:09:52,880 --> 00:09:55,520
"Lock up the office and let's go," I said.
 
 

90
00:09:59,040 --> 00:09:59,680
CHAPTER TWO

91
00:10:00,480 --> 00:10:04,000
Metropolitan Hospital

92
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:09,600
After a few inquiries at the main reception 
desk, we were finally given the location of  

93
00:10:09,600 --> 00:10:16,880
Jose's room at the hospital. Eventually, when we 
reached the floor, it was obvious that gaining  

94
00:10:16,880 --> 00:10:23,360
access would be no simple matter. There was a 
bored-looking police officer sitting outside.  

95
00:10:24,560 --> 00:10:30,640
I thought I might start with a little gentle 
persuasion. It can sometimes work, even on  

96
00:10:30,640 --> 00:10:38,320
police officers. I should know - I used to be 
an NYPD officer before I set up my own business.

97
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:44,160
"Excuse me," I said, showing the 
officer my investigator's license.  

98
00:10:45,200 --> 00:10:47,840
"I represent Mr. Jose De La Cruz.  

99
00:10:48,960 --> 00:10:55,920
Would it be possible to speak to him? The lady 
here is Ms. Delgado, sister of Mr. De La Cruz."

100
00:10:57,360 --> 00:11:02,480
The officer was unimpressed. He 
looked me up and down and said flatly,  

101
00:11:03,360 --> 00:11:07,440
"Sorry, sir. No one's allowed 
in. And that's official."

102
00:11:09,040 --> 00:11:14,320
I wondered if he was going to be one of those 
people who get their job satisfaction by  

103
00:11:14,320 --> 00:11:20,320
creating difficulties for others. I wasn't 
going to take 'no' as the final answer.  

104
00:11:21,520 --> 00:11:25,520
"Come on, now. Just a quick 
word. Won't do any harm."

105
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:33,360
"No," replied the officer sharply. "This 
guy's a suspect. He's wanted for questioning."

106
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:40,080
"Suspected of doing what?" I demanded. 
"Has he been charged with any crime?"

107
00:11:41,360 --> 00:11:42,880
"Don't know, and no."

108
00:11:44,400 --> 00:11:49,600
"Thanks for all your co-operation. Give me 
the name of your boss, will you?" I asked.

109
00:11:50,880 --> 00:11:58,720
It was Captain Oldenberg. A familiar name. 
Oldenberg and I had worked together at the NYPD.  

110
00:11:59,920 --> 00:12:06,240
That was over fifteen years ago, when we'd both 
been patrolmen on the streets of the Lower East  

111
00:12:06,240 --> 00:12:15,120
Side. Since I'd left the NYPD to become a private 
eye, Oldenberg had risen through the ranks and had  

112
00:12:15,120 --> 00:12:24,080
now been promoted to captain. Every now and then 
our professional paths crossed. Oldenberg was the  

113
00:12:24,080 --> 00:12:31,360
sort of guy you didn't forget in a hurry. He could 
be bad- tempered, loud, and dominating at times.  

114
00:12:32,240 --> 00:12:38,960
Despite that, he was basically a good cop. I'd 
need all my charm to deal with him, though.

115
00:12:40,240 --> 00:12:42,720
"Thanks. I'll be back," I said.

116
00:12:44,320 --> 00:12:51,600
Stella was looking furious. "Nat! Exactly 
what is going on here?" she demanded as  

117
00:12:51,600 --> 00:12:57,120
we walked away from the room. "Are you 
just going to take 'no' for an answer?"

118
00:12:58,240 --> 00:13:05,840
"Stay calm, Stella. In this situation we need 
friends, not enemies. I'll call Oldenberg."

119
00:13:07,520 --> 00:13:11,760
I phoned police headquarters and was 
put through to Oldenberg's office.  

120
00:13:12,800 --> 00:13:19,840
He wasn't exactly pleased to hear from me. 
That was normal. He was even less pleased  

121
00:13:19,840 --> 00:13:25,520
when I asked if Jose was free to leave once 
the doctors had given him the all clear.

122
00:13:26,640 --> 00:13:33,760
"You've got to be joking, Marley!" he shouted. 
"There's no way I'm going to let that guy out on  

123
00:13:33,760 --> 00:13:40,480
the streets. He's being held on 'reasonable 
suspicion'. I've had a crime scene team  

124
00:13:40,480 --> 00:13:47,840
examining the car De La Cruz was found in, and 
I'm waiting for the results of forensic tests."

125
00:13:48,400 --> 00:13:55,120
Tests to examine what? Bloodstains 
on clothes? DNA? A weapon?  

126
00:13:56,320 --> 00:13:58,800
I tried my charm on Oldenberg again.

127
00:14:00,080 --> 00:14:04,320
"I'd be interested to know what 
those tests would be for," I said.

128
00:14:05,360 --> 00:14:06,320
"Sure you would.  

129
00:14:06,960 --> 00:14:13,680
Marley, you know I can't reveal any details of 
evidence until the suspect has been charged."

130
00:14:15,040 --> 00:14:19,760
It was the answer I'd been expecting. 
No harm in having another try.

131
00:14:20,960 --> 00:14:24,880
"Have you established who was the owner 
of the vehicle?" I asked hopefully.

132
00:14:25,920 --> 00:14:29,840
"Same as my previous answer," he replied bluntly.

133
00:14:30,880 --> 00:14:37,760
I got the impression that the captain was enjoying 
himself. One last attempt to make some progress.

134
00:14:38,960 --> 00:14:46,720
"OK, Oldenberg. I know your position. Rules 
have to be obeyed. But if my client hasn't been  

135
00:14:46,720 --> 00:14:53,440
charged, why can't I speak to him? I have his 
sister with me and she's upset in a big way.  

136
00:14:54,640 --> 00:14:59,280
Just ten minutes? And I'll agree to 
the police officer being present too."

137
00:15:00,720 --> 00:15:06,960
"All right, Marley. Have your ten minutes. I'll 
call the officer and tell him to expect you."

138
00:15:08,480 --> 00:15:15,920
We hurried back to speak to Jose. The officer 
showed us into his room. Jose was sitting up in  

139
00:15:15,920 --> 00:15:23,840
bed, with a bandage around his head and an IV 
drip attached to his arm. There was a hopeless  

140
00:15:23,840 --> 00:15:30,880
expression on his face. Stella went over to 
him, took his hand, and spoke to him gently.

141
00:15:31,920 --> 00:15:33,520
"How are you feeling, Jose?"

142
00:15:34,640 --> 00:15:44,720
"Not great. I'm full of painkillers, but I can 
still feel my head spinning," said Jose. "Stella,  

143
00:15:45,280 --> 00:15:51,600
it's real good to see you. Are you going to get 
me out of here? I haven't done anything wrong."

144
00:15:52,880 --> 00:15:56,160
"You and I both know you 
haven't done anything wrong,"  

145
00:15:56,160 --> 00:16:02,320
she said. "Remember what I told you, 
Jose. You've got to keep holding on."

146
00:16:03,760 --> 00:16:09,280
"So what's the cop doing here, huh?" asked 
Jose, glancing in the direction of the officer.

147
00:16:10,480 --> 00:16:13,120
"We had to agree to the officer being present.  

148
00:16:13,840 --> 00:16:18,960
Jose, this is my boss, Nat 
Marley. He's going to help you."

149
00:16:20,320 --> 00:16:23,280
"I'm sure glad to see you, Nat," said Jose.

150
00:16:24,640 --> 00:16:30,240
"If we're going to help you, you've got to give 
us the whole story. Don't hold anything back."  

151
00:16:30,240 --> 00:16:35,840
I said. "Everything that happened 
from the time you left home yesterday  

152
00:16:35,840 --> 00:16:37,920
until you woke up in this hospital bed."

153
00:16:39,440 --> 00:16:46,000
Jose, with his two friends, Miguel and Carlos, 
took the subway to Coney Island to find work.  

154
00:16:47,120 --> 00:16:53,840
The boss at the diner offered him a job as a 
cook and Jose's buddies were taken on as waiters.  

155
00:16:54,960 --> 00:16:58,880
Jose showed Miguel and Carlos 
around the sights of Coney Island  

156
00:16:58,880 --> 00:17:05,600
during the afternoon. After stopping for food, 
they moved on to Brighton Beach to celebrate.  

157
00:17:07,200 --> 00:17:13,120
By early evening they'd had several drinks in 
bars on Brighton Beach Avenue, in the heart of  

158
00:17:13,120 --> 00:17:22,080
the Russian community. He had a confused memory 
of waking up in a bar. His buddies had gone. Then  

159
00:17:22,800 --> 00:17:28,320
nothing. The next thing he remembered 
was waking up in Metropolitan Hospital.

160
00:17:29,760 --> 00:17:32,400
"You don't remember anything else?" I asked.

161
00:17:33,520 --> 00:17:40,080
"Nothing. It's the honest truth, Nat," 
said Jose. "It's all a black fog."

162
00:17:41,520 --> 00:17:48,560
"Brighton Beach? Kind of an unusual night out for 
three guys from Upper Manhattan, huh?" I asked.

163
00:17:49,680 --> 00:17:54,720
"You're right. At first it felt 
kind of strange for us to be there,"  

164
00:17:54,720 --> 00:18:01,040
said Jose, "but people were nice and didn't 
mind three outsiders having a night out.  

165
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:06,320
One bartender got friendly when we asked 
him about all the different vodkas."

166
00:18:07,680 --> 00:18:13,840
"Now think hard, Jose. Can you 
remember anything else?" I asked.

167
00:18:14,800 --> 00:18:16,320
"Nothing," he replied.

168
00:18:17,600 --> 00:18:19,600
"What happened to Miguel and Carlos?"

169
00:18:20,640 --> 00:18:21,840
"I can't remember."

170
00:18:23,440 --> 00:18:29,600
It didn't look good. Jose had been found 
unconscious at the wheel of a car that wasn't  

171
00:18:29,600 --> 00:18:35,920
his. He had no memory of what had happened 
after passing out in a Brighton Beach bar.

172
00:18:37,520 --> 00:18:43,120
"Jose, I know you don't have a driver's 
license, but can you drive?" I asked.

173
00:18:44,240 --> 00:18:50,960
"No way, Nat. I've never tried. And even if 
I could, I'd have been too drunk to drive."

174
00:18:52,480 --> 00:18:56,400
The police officer interrupted 
us: "Time's up, Mr. Marley."

175
00:18:57,680 --> 00:19:03,360
There wasn't any point in asking for more 
time. I didn't think we were going to learn  

176
00:19:03,360 --> 00:19:10,880
anything more of value. As to what had actually 
happened, it was still a complete mystery.  

177
00:19:12,080 --> 00:19:16,160
Was Jose the victim or was he the guilty party?

178
00:19:17,440 --> 00:19:22,560
My impression of him from our brief 
talk was of a harmless ordinary guy;  

179
00:19:23,520 --> 00:19:28,960
a guy who had gotten into some sort of trouble 
and had no explanation for what had happened.

180
00:19:30,320 --> 00:19:36,640
It wasn't looking good. There was some small 
hope though, since I'd gotten clients out of  

181
00:19:36,640 --> 00:19:44,800
worse situations than this. Jose needed a lawyer, 
urgently, and I knew just the woman for the job:  

182
00:19:45,520 --> 00:19:54,480
Lena Rosenthal. She was capable, intelligent, and 
tough; someone who could stand up to Oldenberg.  

183
00:19:55,760 --> 00:20:02,080
As soon as Jose was charged with a crime, then 
we would have something concrete from the NYPD.  

184
00:20:03,200 --> 00:20:06,160
Otherwise, we were just operating in the dark.

185
00:20:07,760 --> 00:20:15,040
Stella had to get back to her family, so I gave 
her the rest of the day off. I just wished I could  

186
00:20:15,040 --> 00:20:21,360
say something that might give her some comfort. 
But I knew whatever I said would be inadequate.  

187
00:20:22,480 --> 00:20:27,040
Once I had more information, then I 
might be able to offer her some hope.

188
00:20:28,800 --> 00:20:32,080
The next day, the temperature 
was close to freezing.  

189
00:20:32,960 --> 00:20:39,680
A layer of frost covered the windows of cars 
parked on the street overnight. I'd arrived  

190
00:20:39,680 --> 00:20:45,760
at the office early and was just putting the 
breakfast coffee and donuts down on the desk  

191
00:20:45,760 --> 00:20:51,920
when the phone rang. A familiar voice 
barked at me - Captain Oldenberg.

192
00:20:53,280 --> 00:21:00,560
"Marley? Just calling to tell you that your client 
De La Cruz is still being held at the hospital.  

193
00:21:01,520 --> 00:21:05,120
I wanted to get him moved to 
headquarters for further questioning,  

194
00:21:05,760 --> 00:21:11,280
but the doctors insisted he be kept under 
observation. I'm still waiting for the  

195
00:21:11,280 --> 00:21:17,520
results of the tests on bloodstains found on 
his jacket and a wallet in his possession."

196
00:21:18,960 --> 00:21:27,040
Oldenberg had given away a few more details. 
Bloodstains? Things were getting more serious.

197
00:21:28,320 --> 00:21:36,000
In desperation I said: "Oldenberg, my client 
can't drive. And what's more, the alcohol  

198
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:41,360
level from the blood tests should indicate 
he'd have been incapable of driving anyway."

199
00:21:42,720 --> 00:21:45,840
"Marley, don't make me laugh," he replied.

200
00:21:46,960 --> 00:21:49,200
"My client needs to consult his lawyer.  

201
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:55,840
With your permission, I'd like to take her over 
to the hospital this morning. Any objections?"

202
00:21:56,960 --> 00:22:02,320
"Be my guest, Marley. I'll call the officer 
on duty and tell him to expect you."

203
00:22:03,920 --> 00:22:12,480
By now Stella had arrived. I told her the latest 
developments. She took it all in silently then sat  

204
00:22:12,480 --> 00:22:18,800
in front of her computer with her head in her 
hands. I arranged to pick up Lena Rosenthal.

205
00:22:20,160 --> 00:22:24,320
Later, as our cab headed up First 
Avenue towards the hospital,  

206
00:22:24,320 --> 00:22:31,680
I gave Lena all the details she needed about 
Jose's case. I also explained how I was involved.

207
00:22:32,880 --> 00:22:39,840
"Lena, this isn't just a routine case for me. 
This guy's the kid brother of my assistant,  

208
00:22:39,840 --> 00:22:45,840
Stella Delgado. Stella's been working for me 
so long that she's like part of my family.  

209
00:22:46,720 --> 00:22:53,840
I feel responsible for both Stella and Jose. 
You could say it's personal this time."

210
00:22:55,440 --> 00:23:00,400
Lena nodded. "Thanks for telling me, 
Nat. Anything else I should know?"

211
00:23:01,600 --> 00:23:04,080
"I should warn you about Captain Oldenberg.  

212
00:23:04,880 --> 00:23:08,480
He has a reputation for being 
aggressive and insensitive."

213
00:23:09,760 --> 00:23:15,440
"Oldenberg and I have met before. I 
know what to expect," replied Lena.

214
00:23:16,960 --> 00:23:21,840
At the hospital, before we saw 
Jose, a doctor took us aside.

215
00:23:23,120 --> 00:23:25,840
"Excuse me. Are you family?" she asked.

216
00:23:26,960 --> 00:23:33,840
"We represent Mr. De La Cruz. The name's Nat 
Marley, private investigator," I replied,  

217
00:23:33,840 --> 00:23:39,920
flashing my I.D. at the doctor. "This 
is his lawyer Ms. Rosenthal. We have  

218
00:23:39,920 --> 00:23:43,120
permission from the NYPD to visit our client."

219
00:23:44,320 --> 00:23:51,280
"Thank you. I'm Dr. Ericson. Mr. De La Cruz 
has been under my care since he was admitted.  

220
00:23:52,160 --> 00:23:59,280
His condition has been giving me cause for 
concern. In the accident, he received a heavy blow  

221
00:23:59,280 --> 00:24:06,880
to the head. So far his condition has been stable, 
but there have been some symptoms that worry me.  

222
00:24:07,840 --> 00:24:15,040
He's complained about seeing double images and he 
has twice lost consciousness, though very briefly.  

223
00:24:16,160 --> 00:24:22,640
And also there's some memory loss. So, I 
must warn you not to put Mr. De La Cruz  

224
00:24:22,640 --> 00:24:29,280
under any unnecessary stress. He's been through 
enough already, and with any further stress..."

225
00:24:30,160 --> 00:24:32,800
"Understood, Doctor. We'll take great care."

226
00:24:34,400 --> 00:24:40,480
Before seeing Jose, Lena turned to 
me. "It would be a good idea not to  

227
00:24:40,480 --> 00:24:46,240
mention anything about the forensic tests. 
This guy sounds scared enough already."

228
00:24:47,360 --> 00:24:48,720
I nodded my agreement.

229
00:24:50,400 --> 00:24:57,360
Eventually we were allowed in to speak 
to Jose. He looked at us with dull eyes  

230
00:24:57,360 --> 00:25:02,640
and raised a hand to acknowledge us. 
I could see the despair in his eyes.  

231
00:25:04,080 --> 00:25:08,400
Lena went over exactly the same 
questions as I had asked before.  

232
00:25:09,680 --> 00:25:17,760
There was nothing more that Jose could add. We 
had made no further progress. As we were leaving,  

233
00:25:18,320 --> 00:25:28,560
Jose cried out hopelessly: "Nat, for God's sake, 
get me out of here! I'm going out of my mind."
 
 

234
00:25:32,320 --> 00:25:33,120
CHAPTER THREE

235
00:25:33,920 --> 00:25:34,800
Jones Beach

236
00:25:36,960 --> 00:25:42,720
Saturday morning was cold but 
bright. I was feeling fit and active.  

237
00:25:44,080 --> 00:25:50,960
I started the day by following my Saturday 
routine. Buying the Daily News and wandering  

238
00:25:50,960 --> 00:25:59,200
down Main Street, Queens, to Slim Pete's Diner. 
Breakfast there was always reliable - unhealthy  

239
00:25:59,760 --> 00:26:05,680
but very tasty. Maybe that explained 
'Slim' Pete's weight problem.

240
00:26:07,280 --> 00:26:11,280
"Morning, Nat," said Slim Pete. "Why so cheerful?"

241
00:26:12,560 --> 00:26:20,720
"Pete, I now realize that a healthy lifestyle is 
no solution to a mid-life crisis - which means  

242
00:26:20,720 --> 00:26:24,480
I'll have one of your breakfast 
specials and plenty of coffee."

243
00:26:26,080 --> 00:26:30,640
As I worked my way through breakfast, 
I looked through the Daily News.  

244
00:26:31,680 --> 00:26:37,840
There was a story about a murder victim. 
A guy by the name of Alexei Romanov.  

245
00:26:39,040 --> 00:26:46,400
Where had I heard the name 'Romanov' before? 
That was it, the old Russian royal family.  

246
00:26:47,680 --> 00:26:55,120
The body had been found late Friday afternoon, 
floating in Coney Island Creek. The victim had  

247
00:26:55,120 --> 00:27:02,640
been shot in the head and had been dead for over 
twenty-four hours. There were some more details.  

248
00:27:03,840 --> 00:27:09,360
Romanov owned some kind of business on 
Brighton Beach. He was involved in a  

249
00:27:09,360 --> 00:27:15,200
society that helped immigrants from Russia 
to settle and adapt to life in the U.S.A.  

250
00:27:16,480 --> 00:27:22,720
His tearful widow told reporters that she 
had no idea who could have done such a thing.  

251
00:27:23,760 --> 00:27:27,840
He seemed to have been a 
well-liked and respected man  

252
00:27:27,840 --> 00:27:34,320
who was active in the community. I hoped and 
prayed there was no connection with Jose.

253
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:43,680
Another story caught my eye. The headline 
read: 'Wreck on Jones Beach'. Part of  

254
00:27:43,680 --> 00:27:49,280
a lifeboat had been washed up on the 
shore. Two bodies had been found nearby.  

255
00:27:50,480 --> 00:27:57,040
No further details. I'd been brought 
up on Staten Island. As a kid,  

256
00:27:57,760 --> 00:28:05,600
just taking the ferry across to Manhattan seemed 
like a big adventure. A day out on Coney Island  

257
00:28:05,600 --> 00:28:12,400
was a real trip, but Jones Beach, on 
Long Island, felt like going abroad.  

258
00:28:13,920 --> 00:28:21,280
Maybe there's something of that kid still left 
inside me. I still get a thrill when I get way  

259
00:28:21,280 --> 00:28:28,080
out of the city and stand on the beach looking 
out at the Atlantic, watching the waves crashing.  

260
00:28:29,440 --> 00:28:34,560
Why not escape from the city for the 
day? The ocean air would do me good.

261
00:28:36,160 --> 00:28:40,320
I was folding up the newspaper 
when Slim Pete came over to chat.

262
00:28:41,600 --> 00:28:48,800
"So what's New York's smartest private eye doing? 
Putting more gangsters behind bars?" he asked.

263
00:28:50,080 --> 00:28:55,680
"Funny you should say that," I answered. 
"New York's criminal community can relax.  

264
00:28:56,480 --> 00:29:00,080
I've just decided I'm going 
to spend a day at the beach."

265
00:29:01,240 --> 00:29:06,000
"Huh! A life of leisure. It's 
all right for some people."

266
00:29:07,440 --> 00:29:13,600
I took the bus from Main Street, to Jamaica 
Station. You can connect there with the Long  

267
00:29:13,600 --> 00:29:22,560
Island Rail Road to Freeport. From there, I took 
a cab to Jones Beach, a long narrow strip of land  

268
00:29:22,560 --> 00:29:29,200
about two miles from the mainland. There was a 
real chill in the wind coming in off the ocean.  

269
00:29:30,080 --> 00:29:36,160
Enough to keep any crowds away so early 
in the year. In the height of the season,  

270
00:29:36,800 --> 00:29:42,080
thousands of New Yorkers crowd into the 
area to claim their little piece of beach.  

271
00:29:43,120 --> 00:29:48,800
But today I could walk without tripping 
over beach towels or bumping into umbrellas.

272
00:29:50,240 --> 00:29:57,040
I strolled along the shore for about an hour, 
then returned. Unusually energetic for me,  

273
00:29:57,680 --> 00:30:02,080
but I felt better afterwards. 
The air was clean and fresh.  

274
00:30:03,280 --> 00:30:09,120
Then I stood for a while on the Atlantic 
side, watching the waves crash onto the beach.  

275
00:30:10,560 --> 00:30:17,200
I knew why I had really come here. It was the 
reports of the bodies washed up on the beach.  

276
00:30:18,320 --> 00:30:22,560
It was my day off, but I was 
still playing the investigator.  

277
00:30:23,680 --> 00:30:30,480
That was why my marriage had broken up. My wife 
never saw much of me when I was with the NYPD.  

278
00:30:31,760 --> 00:30:39,120
When I started out on my own as a private 
investigator she saw even less of me. Then  

279
00:30:39,120 --> 00:30:45,920
one day she walked out on me. She left a 
note which said that I just didn't give her  

280
00:30:45,920 --> 00:30:53,600
enough attention and she couldn't carry on 
like that. The sad truth was she was right.  

281
00:30:54,880 --> 00:31:01,600
If there's ever a second Mrs. Marley, she'll have 
to be one very tolerant lady to put up with me.

282
00:31:03,280 --> 00:31:06,800
I wandered over to a group of bars and restaurants  

283
00:31:06,800 --> 00:31:09,360
which would be packed with 
visitors in a few weeks.  

284
00:31:10,640 --> 00:31:17,840
One or two were already open, while in others work 
was going on in preparation for the coming season.  

285
00:31:19,200 --> 00:31:25,760
Outside a bar an old guy up on a ladder was 
painting. He looked down at me from his work.

286
00:31:26,960 --> 00:31:34,320
"You're out of luck if you want a drink, mister. 
We don't open till the first of April," he said.

287
00:31:35,520 --> 00:31:39,680
"Just wanted to talk if it's 
not holding you up," I replied.

288
00:31:41,040 --> 00:31:46,480
"Go ahead and talk, mister. I'm just 
doing this as a favor for my son-in-law.  

289
00:31:47,360 --> 00:31:49,680
He doesn't care how slowly I work."

290
00:31:51,200 --> 00:31:53,600
"I see Jones Beach has been in the news.  

291
00:31:54,640 --> 00:32:00,800
Some story about a lifeboat found wrecked 
along the shore and two bodies," I said.

292
00:32:02,160 --> 00:32:06,000
The old man came down from 
the ladder. A good sign.  

293
00:32:06,720 --> 00:32:14,000
I had got his interest. He pointed west 
along the shore with a dripping paintbrush.

294
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:21,840
"The wrecked lifeboat was found about a mile 
west along the beach. There's an old lady - when  

295
00:32:21,840 --> 00:32:28,880
I say old, she's a good ten years older than 
me. Well, she goes beachcombing regularly.  

296
00:32:29,520 --> 00:32:34,960
You know, looking for shells and stuff. 
She found the wreck and the bodies."

297
00:32:36,160 --> 00:32:40,000
"Really! Must have been quite 
a shock for her," I said.

298
00:32:41,200 --> 00:32:47,680
"I don't know about that, mister. It 
made her day. Never seen her so excited."

299
00:32:49,040 --> 00:32:53,920
It was time to make my move. I 
showed him my investigator's license.

300
00:32:55,040 --> 00:33:02,480
"Gee! A real private eye!" exclaimed the 
old man. "I would've expected someone..."

301
00:33:03,120 --> 00:33:06,080
"Someone younger and 
better-looking?" I interrupted.  

302
00:33:07,280 --> 00:33:14,320
"We come in all shapes and sizes. Look, 
I'm investigating this wreck for a client,"  

303
00:33:14,320 --> 00:33:20,560
I lied. "I'd like to talk to this lady. 
Who is she, and where can I find her?"

304
00:33:21,600 --> 00:33:29,440
"Her name's Edith Tilden. People call her 'Edie'. 
She's English, but she's lived here for years.  

305
00:33:30,160 --> 00:33:37,840
She looks kind of eccentric, but she's OK once 
you get talking. See that place over there?"

306
00:33:38,720 --> 00:33:42,240
The old man pointed toward a 
beat-up building with the sign  

307
00:33:42,880 --> 00:33:46,160
'Ornella's Italian Clam House' above the entrance.

308
00:33:47,520 --> 00:33:50,640
"She'll probably be in there," he continued.  

309
00:33:51,360 --> 00:33:57,120
"She claims Ornella's the only person on 
Jones Beach who can make a good cup of tea."

310
00:33:58,640 --> 00:34:03,680
Life's full of surprises. Since 
when did Italians make good tea?  

311
00:34:05,120 --> 00:34:11,680
I entered the restaurant. It didn't look open 
for business. Most of the tables and chairs  

312
00:34:11,680 --> 00:34:19,280
were piled up in a corner. Only a handful of 
tables were set. At one of the tables sat a  

313
00:34:19,280 --> 00:34:26,160
little old lady dressed in bright yellow and 
purple. A plump, cheerful woman welcomed me.

314
00:34:27,280 --> 00:34:35,200
"Morning, mister. No hot food until April. 
Just snacks and hot and cold drinks." she said.

315
00:34:36,400 --> 00:34:41,120
"I was looking for a sandwich and 
a cup of tea. I've been told that  

316
00:34:41,120 --> 00:34:44,720
you make the best tea in Jones Beach," I replied.

317
00:34:45,920 --> 00:34:51,520
The old woman at the table looked up and said, 
"You've come to the right place for tea."

318
00:34:52,880 --> 00:34:56,480
"Then make that two teas - one for the lady here."

319
00:34:58,080 --> 00:35:06,720
I went over to her table. "Mind if I join you?" I 
asked. "Not at all," she answered. "Take a seat."

320
00:35:07,920 --> 00:35:12,880
I noticed the way she spoke. Not 
the slightest American accent.

321
00:35:14,160 --> 00:35:16,880
"Thanks. You English?" I asked.

322
00:35:17,840 --> 00:35:25,040
"I'm probably as American as you are, now. 
I've been in the U.S.A. for fifty years  

323
00:35:25,040 --> 00:35:32,000
but never lost the accent or the tea-drinking 
habit. The name's Edie, Edie Tilden."

324
00:35:33,280 --> 00:35:35,840
"Pleased to meet you. I'm Nat Marley."

325
00:35:37,280 --> 00:35:40,080
The sandwich and teas were 
brought over to the table.  

326
00:35:41,200 --> 00:35:45,440
After small talk about the weather, 
it was time to get some information.  

327
00:35:46,720 --> 00:35:54,080
I showed Edie my private investigator's license. 
Her eyes grew large and round and her mouth  

328
00:35:54,080 --> 00:36:01,440
dropped open. This old lady was deeply impressed. 
I wish I had that effect on people more often.

329
00:36:02,880 --> 00:36:07,040
"I hear you found the wrecked 
lifeboat and two bodies on the beach.  

330
00:36:07,920 --> 00:36:11,840
I'm investigating the wreck 
for a client," I lied again.

331
00:36:12,960 --> 00:36:15,520
Edie waved her teaspoon at me excitedly.  

332
00:36:16,560 --> 00:36:24,240
"Mr. Marley, I've been walking up and down 
this beach for years. I've found bits and  

333
00:36:24,240 --> 00:36:33,920
pieces of boats, but never a body. Two real dead 
bodies! What do you say to that?" she asked.

334
00:36:35,200 --> 00:36:37,920
"Must have been a terrible shock," I said.

335
00:36:39,040 --> 00:36:42,400
"People don't look pretty 
after they've been in the sea."

336
00:36:43,840 --> 00:36:45,840
"Can you describe them?" I asked.

337
00:36:46,880 --> 00:36:54,240
"Certainly. Two young men, could be 
anywhere in their twenties. Medium height.  

338
00:36:54,240 --> 00:37:02,800
Thin. Both of them looked as if they needed a good 
meal. Short hair. They hadn't shaved for days.  

339
00:37:03,760 --> 00:37:09,520
Cheap-looking clothes. One of them had 
a gold cross on a chain around his neck.  

340
00:37:10,320 --> 00:37:14,080
I've never seen one like it 
before. Let me show you."

341
00:37:15,360 --> 00:37:22,000
She paused, took a clean paper napkin from 
the table, found a pencil in her pocket,  

342
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:28,160
and drew a picture of a cross with two 
horizontal bars, the top one a little shorter.  

343
00:37:29,200 --> 00:37:37,360
Then at the base of the cross, a short bar at a 
forty-five degree angle. I didn't recognize it.

344
00:37:38,720 --> 00:37:45,760
"Thanks. Mind if I keep this?" I asked. 
"Now what can you remember about the boat?"

345
00:37:46,960 --> 00:37:50,160
"What I found was the rear half.  

346
00:37:50,160 --> 00:37:57,120
Probably from a boat big enough to fit a dozen 
people in. It had seen better days, though."

347
00:37:58,080 --> 00:37:58,880
"What do you mean?"

348
00:38:00,080 --> 00:38:08,720
"The wood was rotten with age. Some of it was so 
soft I could break off pieces with my bare hands.  

349
00:38:09,600 --> 00:38:12,960
It looked like someone had 
been trying to repair it,  

350
00:38:12,960 --> 00:38:18,000
but hadn't made a good job of it. 
The boat must have split in two."

351
00:38:19,360 --> 00:38:24,720
"Were there any identifying marks? 
Like names or numbers?" I asked.

352
00:38:25,680 --> 00:38:33,200
"Some letters at the back, maybe the boat's 
name," Edie answered. "I couldn't make out  

353
00:38:33,200 --> 00:38:40,080
a complete word, but it looked like a foreign 
language. And that's about all I can tell you.  

354
00:38:40,880 --> 00:38:46,000
The Coast Guard took it away 
so there's nothing to see now.

355
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:48,480
"Thanks. You've been very helpful.  

356
00:38:49,200 --> 00:38:54,480
Here's my card. Where can I contact 
you if I need to speak to you again?"

357
00:38:56,160 --> 00:39:02,960
She wrote a Freeport address and phone number on 
the paper. I left Edie and did some more beach  

358
00:39:02,960 --> 00:39:09,200
walking. I felt relaxed and content when 
I finally got back to Queens that evening.  

359
00:39:10,640 --> 00:39:12,720
But there was still the problem of Jose.  

360
00:39:13,840 --> 00:39:19,760
Unless I turned up some new evidence soon, 
he could be facing a long prison sentence.

361
00:39:21,520 --> 00:39:28,400
The next day I woke up early but was feeling 
active. It must have been the effect of all that  

362
00:39:28,400 --> 00:39:36,880
exercise the day before. There are various ways 
to spend your Sunday. Unfortunately, I had to  

363
00:39:36,880 --> 00:39:44,240
go into the office to sort out some accounts. On 
the subway, I glanced through the Sunday edition  

364
00:39:44,240 --> 00:39:51,440
of the Daily News. It didn't have anything to 
add to yesterday's stories. At the office on  

365
00:39:51,440 --> 00:39:57,760
East 43rd Street, I was trying to make sense of 
the previous year's accounts when the phone rang.  

366
00:39:58,720 --> 00:40:07,280
Who on earth wanted to speak to me at this time on 
a Sunday? I grabbed the phone. It was Oldenberg.

367
00:40:08,640 --> 00:40:12,000
"Marley, trust you to be 
in the office on a Sunday.  

368
00:40:12,720 --> 00:40:15,520
Just wanted to bring you 
up to date on your client."

369
00:40:16,640 --> 00:40:20,720
I immediately felt tense. "Go on," I said.

370
00:40:21,680 --> 00:40:24,480
"I'm on my way back from Metropolitan  

371
00:40:24,480 --> 00:40:30,720
Hospital," said Oldenberg. "De La 
Cruz has been charged with murder."
 
 

372
00:40:34,160 --> 00:40:34,960
CHAPTER FOUR

373
00:40:35,840 --> 00:40:37,840
East Harlem

374
00:40:38,720 --> 00:40:45,680
"Oldenberg," I began, "you've got a confused guy 
in a hospital bed with serious head injuries,  

375
00:40:46,240 --> 00:40:49,360
and you add to the misery with a murder charge!"

376
00:40:50,480 --> 00:40:55,760
"Just doing my job, Marley," he 
replied. "Following procedure."

377
00:40:57,040 --> 00:40:59,280
"Who's the murder victim?" I asked.

378
00:41:00,240 --> 00:41:06,160
"A guy by the name of Alexei Romanov, 
some businessman from Brighton Beach."

379
00:41:07,520 --> 00:41:10,400
The same guy I'd read about in the Daily News.  

380
00:41:11,600 --> 00:41:18,080
"OK, Oldenberg. You'd better explain how you 
reached the conclusion that my client's a killer."

381
00:41:19,440 --> 00:41:26,160
Oldenberg went on to give me the details. 
The cause of death was a shot to the head  

382
00:41:26,160 --> 00:41:32,480
from the pistol which was found in the car. Jose's 
fingerprints were on the handle and trigger.  

383
00:41:33,520 --> 00:41:40,720
The results of the forensic tests proved 
that he was the attacker. Romanov's blood  

384
00:41:40,720 --> 00:41:48,640
was found on Jose's jacket. Also, the NYPD 
had positive identification of a wallet  

385
00:41:48,640 --> 00:41:57,200
found in his possession - it belonged to Romanov. 
The police had the murder weapon, the killer,  

386
00:41:57,840 --> 00:42:04,720
and forensic evidence. As far as Oldenberg 
was concerned, the investigation was closed.  

387
00:42:05,920 --> 00:42:13,200
I had serious doubts. All the evidence 
pointed toward Jose, but what was the motive?

388
00:42:14,880 --> 00:42:18,960
"OK, Oldenberg. Have you 
established a motive?" I asked.

389
00:42:19,920 --> 00:42:26,480
"Maybe he saw the opportunity to get some easy 
money - a carjacking, I guess," he answered.

390
00:42:27,760 --> 00:42:29,840
Again, I wasn't convinced.  

391
00:42:30,720 --> 00:42:37,760
Could a sleepy drunk possibly be capable of 
carjacking and murder? "What do you mean,  

392
00:42:37,760 --> 00:42:43,840
'I guess'? Where's the supporting 
evidence? Do you have witnesses?" I asked.

393
00:42:44,880 --> 00:42:50,480
"Who needs witnesses with the amount of 
evidence piled up against him?" Oldenberg asked.

394
00:42:51,840 --> 00:42:58,400
No point in continuing the conversation. 
I'd learned enough. The significant point  

395
00:42:58,400 --> 00:43:03,920
was the lack of witnesses. Oldenberg 
obviously thought that the forensic  

396
00:43:03,920 --> 00:43:11,200
evidence was enough to prove Jose was guilty. 
Someone must have seen Jose and his buddies  

397
00:43:11,200 --> 00:43:17,760
celebrating that night. I'd have to go to 
Brighton Beach to do some of my own investigating.

398
00:43:19,360 --> 00:43:26,080
Meanwhile, I needed to check on Jose. A call 
to the hospital confirmed that his condition  

399
00:43:26,080 --> 00:43:30,560
was stable, but the doctors were 
still keeping him under observation.  

400
00:43:31,840 --> 00:43:37,920
It seemed unlikely that he would be allowed 
to leave the hospital. But Jose was better off  

401
00:43:37,920 --> 00:43:46,880
there than in a cell. Another call, this time to 
Stella. I brought her up to date on developments.  

402
00:43:47,920 --> 00:43:55,040
I also needed to get a clearer picture of exactly 
what had happened on Wednesday night. I had to  

403
00:43:55,040 --> 00:44:02,160
speak to one of Jose's buddies. Stella promised 
to set up a meeting with them as soon as possible.

404
00:44:03,280 --> 00:44:05,840
A few minutes later, Stella called back.

405
00:44:07,120 --> 00:44:14,720
"Nat? I've set up a meeting with Carlos and 
Miguel. Can you get over here now?... Yes?...  

406
00:44:15,680 --> 00:44:25,600
Good. We'll be at my mom's apartment, 1295 
First Ave, apartment 104, on the tenth floor.  

407
00:44:26,720 --> 00:44:33,840
That's the East River Housing, on First 
Avenue between 102nd and 105th Streets.  

408
00:44:34,640 --> 00:44:40,400
We'll be expecting you. Call me on my cell 
phone if you have any problem finding it.

409
00:44:41,840 --> 00:44:47,920
There wouldn't be any problem. The area 
was Spanish Harlem, and I'd walked most  

410
00:44:47,920 --> 00:44:55,680
of those streets when I was an NYPD patrolman. 
My only hope was that his buddies would remember  

411
00:44:55,680 --> 00:45:04,080
something that had slipped Jose's mind, anything. 
I took an uptown local train from Grand Central  

412
00:45:04,080 --> 00:45:11,120
to 103rd Street, then walked the three blocks 
across town to the East River Housing project.  

413
00:45:12,240 --> 00:45:19,760
In the space of those seven subway stops, the 
city changes completely. In Spanish Harlem,  

414
00:45:19,760 --> 00:45:26,640
there's not a skyscraper in sight. Only a 
few remaining traditional brownstone houses  

415
00:45:26,640 --> 00:45:32,240
among the anonymous gray concrete 
blocks of the housing projects.

416
00:45:32,240 --> 00:45:35,280
I was shown into a comfortably furnished room  

417
00:45:35,280 --> 00:45:40,480
overlooking the East River, with a view of 
Wards Island at the southern tip of the Bronx.  

418
00:45:41,600 --> 00:45:46,880
Jose's buddies were there. Two 
ordinary-looking guys in their early twenties.

419
00:45:48,080 --> 00:45:54,160
Stella introduced us. "Nat. I'd 
like you to meet Miguel and Carlos.  

420
00:45:55,040 --> 00:46:02,080
This is my boss, Nat. He's like family to me, 
and we're doing everything we can to help Jose.  

421
00:46:03,120 --> 00:46:07,120
I want you to tell everything to 
Nat just like you told it to me."

422
00:46:08,320 --> 00:46:11,120
"All of it? Again?" asked Carlos.

423
00:46:12,160 --> 00:46:17,680
"Yes, every bit. You might recall 
something that could help Jose," she said.

424
00:46:19,200 --> 00:46:27,120
Carlos began. Much of what they said confirmed 
what we already knew from Jose's story: the  

425
00:46:27,120 --> 00:46:33,680
interview at the diner, the sightseeing tour of 
Coney Island, the bars on Brighton Beach Avenue.  

426
00:46:35,040 --> 00:46:42,240
What I was really interested in was the 
final bar where Jose had fallen asleep.

427
00:46:42,240 --> 00:46:46,720
"We ended up in this bar that had 
every kind of vodka you could imagine,"  

428
00:46:46,720 --> 00:46:52,800
continued Carlos. "The bartender in there got 
friendly when we took an interest in the drinks.  

429
00:46:53,600 --> 00:46:55,840
He was recommending what to try."

430
00:46:56,800 --> 00:46:59,040
"The name of the bar?" I asked.

431
00:47:00,240 --> 00:47:04,000
"Sorry, Nat. I don't remember," replied Carlos.

432
00:47:05,440 --> 00:47:13,520
"So, some bar, somewhere in Brighton Beach, 
selling lots of different vodkas. Could be  

433
00:47:13,520 --> 00:47:20,160
one of many in New York's Little Odessa. Can 
you remember anything else about the bar?"

434
00:47:21,600 --> 00:47:27,920
"The walls were covered with baseball 
stuff. Team photos, shirts, bats...  

435
00:47:27,920 --> 00:47:35,040
that sort of thing. I remember asking the 
bartender, 'Hey, what's all this? Baseball  

436
00:47:35,040 --> 00:47:40,640
in the middle of the Russian community?' 
Apparently the owner's a huge baseball fan."

437
00:47:41,840 --> 00:47:50,080
"Good," I said. "There can't be too many bars like 
that in Little Odessa. How long did you stay?"

438
00:47:51,280 --> 00:47:57,520
"We tried all these different flavored vodkas. 
After an hour or so, I knew I'd had too much.  

439
00:47:58,400 --> 00:48:06,480
My head was spinning. Jose had fallen asleep, 
and I knew we'd have to help him home. We needed  

440
00:48:06,480 --> 00:48:12,080
to get sober for the subway ride, so Miguel 
and I went out to find some black coffee.  

441
00:48:13,120 --> 00:48:19,520
We found a place that had coffee to go. 
Carlos waited outside the bar with the coffees  

442
00:48:19,520 --> 00:48:26,800
while I went inside to get Jose. But there 
was no sign of him. I asked the bartender,  

443
00:48:26,800 --> 00:48:31,600
but he didn't know. We just thought 
he'd woken up and gone home."

444
00:48:32,880 --> 00:48:38,880
"Thanks. You've been a great help. Call 
Stella if you remember anything more," I said.

445
00:48:40,480 --> 00:48:48,800
Progress at last. I now had a starting point 
for my investigation. I had to find the bar  

446
00:48:48,800 --> 00:48:56,000
that Jose and his friends had gone to. 
Now I had a lead: the baseball connection.  

447
00:48:57,360 --> 00:49:01,840
Suddenly, my cell phone rang. 
It was Captain Oldenberg.

448
00:49:02,800 --> 00:49:10,960
"Marley? It's your client De La Cruz. The guy's 
gone crazy. He broke out of an operating room  

449
00:49:10,960 --> 00:49:17,120
and somehow climbed up on the roof of the 
hospital. He's threatening to throw himself off.  

450
00:49:18,080 --> 00:49:23,680
He might listen to you. Can you come right 
now and help talk some sense into him?"
 
 

451
00:49:27,200 --> 00:49:28,080
CHAPTER FIVE

452
00:49:28,800 --> 00:49:31,520
A matter of life or death

453
00:49:33,680 --> 00:49:41,360
Metropolitan Hospital is only three blocks 
downtown on First Avenue. Stella ran on ahead  

454
00:49:41,360 --> 00:49:46,400
and I hurried after her. I was 
completely out of breath when I arrived.  

455
00:49:47,840 --> 00:49:54,320
Outside the main entrance was a collection of 
various NYPD vehicles and a Fire Department truck  

456
00:49:54,320 --> 00:50:00,560
with a ladder. Barriers had been set up around 
the base of the building with signs that read:  

457
00:50:01,120 --> 00:50:08,720
'Police line. Do not cross.' High up on the top 
of the building, sitting on the edge of the roof,  

458
00:50:09,280 --> 00:50:16,960
I could make out a figure. It was Jose. If 
he jumped, there was no way he'd survive.

459
00:50:18,560 --> 00:50:24,160
Among the police vehicles was a large 
blue van marked 'Tactical Response Unit.'  

460
00:50:25,200 --> 00:50:32,320
That's police language, which translated means 
'a negotiation team.' These are the people whose  

461
00:50:32,320 --> 00:50:41,280
weapons are words, not guns. They will negotiate 
for hours or days to prevent a crime or a tragedy.  

462
00:50:42,480 --> 00:50:49,200
I was relieved to see them here. Those guys are 
so calm compared to officers like Oldenberg.  

463
00:50:50,000 --> 00:50:52,480
They wouldn't get impatient watching paint dry.  

464
00:50:53,680 --> 00:50:57,360
If it takes forty-eight hours 
to prevent a potential death by  

465
00:50:57,360 --> 00:51:05,920
talking to the guy, hour after hour, they'll do 
it. Persuasion, not force, is their philosophy.

466
00:51:07,440 --> 00:51:10,240
Oldenberg was waiting for us outside the entrance.  

467
00:51:11,440 --> 00:51:16,080
"Er, Marley," he began, "this 
is kind of embarrassing..."

468
00:51:17,120 --> 00:51:26,160
I cut him off. "Embarrassing? It's a disaster! 
How on earth did my client end up on the roof?"  

469
00:51:26,160 --> 00:51:30,640
I demanded. "I thought you had 
him under twenty-four-hour guard.  

470
00:51:31,520 --> 00:51:37,920
What's been going on here? Is this 
another example of NYPD inefficiency?"

471
00:51:39,520 --> 00:51:44,480
As we hurried through the hospital corridors, 
Oldenberg raised his hands in apology.  

472
00:51:45,520 --> 00:51:52,720
"I can't offer any excuses. Your client had been 
taken to an operating room. The police officer  

473
00:51:52,720 --> 00:52:01,120
was told that De La Cruz was unconscious, so he 
decided to take an unofficial break outside. The  

474
00:52:01,120 --> 00:52:06,640
medical team had to leave De La Cruz temporarily 
while they attended to a more urgent case.  

475
00:52:07,680 --> 00:52:13,040
During that time, he must have regained 
consciousness, panicked and gone up to the roof."

476
00:52:14,560 --> 00:52:22,480
An elevator took us up to the top floor. We were 
taken through a door marked: 'No entry.' At the  

477
00:52:22,480 --> 00:52:28,720
foot of the stairs to the roof, Dr. Ericson 
was waiting. She looked nervous and anxious.

478
00:52:30,080 --> 00:52:37,200
"Mr. Marley and Ms. Delgado, thank God you're 
here. My patient needs people he knows and trusts.  

479
00:52:38,160 --> 00:52:44,480
You know he should be in the operating room? He 
was being prepared for surgery before escaping  

480
00:52:44,480 --> 00:52:48,480
wearing only a surgical gown. He's seriously ill.  

481
00:52:49,440 --> 00:52:54,400
I'm not trying to be dramatic, but 
this is a matter of life or death."

482
00:52:56,240 --> 00:53:00,240
"Thanks, Doctor. I understand 
your concern," I said.

483
00:53:01,360 --> 00:53:07,440
"One more thing, Mr. Marley. There are some 
curious bruise marks on Mr. De La Cruz's neck.  

484
00:53:08,320 --> 00:53:10,880
Like someone had gripped him violently.  

485
00:53:11,600 --> 00:53:14,880
He couldn't have received injuries 
like that in a car crash."

486
00:53:16,080 --> 00:53:19,840
The doctor put her fingers and thumb 
around her throat to demonstrate.

487
00:53:21,040 --> 00:53:25,040
"I told Captain Oldenberg, but he 
didn't seem to take any notice.  

488
00:53:25,840 --> 00:53:27,840
I don't like that man's attitude."

489
00:53:28,640 --> 00:53:33,760
"Me neither," I replied. "Thanks for 
telling me. It could be very important."

490
00:53:35,360 --> 00:53:43,120
We climbed the stairs to the roof. Outside, 
the wind was bitterly cold. A woman was sitting  

491
00:53:43,120 --> 00:53:50,160
on a low wall a few yards away from Jose. 
Detective Valdez from the negotiation team.  

492
00:53:51,680 --> 00:53:57,280
Jose was sitting on the wall, wrapped 
up in a blanket from the operating room,  

493
00:53:57,280 --> 00:53:59,680
with one leg hanging over the edge.

494
00:54:01,120 --> 00:54:08,960
Stella and I cautiously made our way along the 
roof. I don't like heights, especially when the  

495
00:54:08,960 --> 00:54:15,520
only protection from a fatal drop is a 
knee-high wall. We sat down beside her.

496
00:54:16,720 --> 00:54:22,160
"Mr. Marley and Ms. Delgado?" she said in a 
whisper, with her face turned away from Jose.  

497
00:54:23,200 --> 00:54:29,760
"I'm very relieved to see you here. The 
more people there are around that Jose knows  

498
00:54:29,760 --> 00:54:34,000
and trusts, the more likely we 
are to talk him off the roof.  

499
00:54:35,120 --> 00:54:39,520
Just keep your distance from him 
until he's ready to speak to you."

500
00:54:40,800 --> 00:54:47,120
"Jose knows us as Nat and Stella. Are 
there any other officers up here?" I asked.

501
00:54:48,160 --> 00:54:54,400
"No. I tried to get more in position, but 
Jose noticed them and started to panic.  

502
00:54:55,360 --> 00:55:01,760
So I insisted on just one officer, 
and here I am," Valdez explained.

503
00:55:03,120 --> 00:55:10,160
In situations like this, you never know whether 
a suicide threat is a desperate call for help,  

504
00:55:10,160 --> 00:55:15,840
or if it's the real thing. It's a 
situation where nobody can take chances.  

505
00:55:16,800 --> 00:55:24,800
The consequences could be disastrous. Detective 
Valdez continued with the routine that has saved  

506
00:55:24,800 --> 00:55:31,520
countless lives in this city. The technique 
was to establish a relationship and gain trust.

507
00:55:32,960 --> 00:55:38,400
"Jose, you know who I am now. 
I just want to talk," she said.

508
00:55:39,680 --> 00:55:47,920
No response from Jose. He put the blanket over 
his head, so his face was hidden from view.

509
00:55:47,920 --> 00:55:54,080
"I just want to know if you're listening. Raise 
a hand if you're listening to me," she asked.

510
00:55:55,360 --> 00:56:04,240
Jose briefly raised his right hand. She continued 
in the same smooth, calm voice. "I've got some  

511
00:56:04,240 --> 00:56:11,440
friends of yours here, Stella and Nat. They're 
worried about you. Do you want to speak to them?"

512
00:56:12,720 --> 00:56:15,920
Again, no response.

513
00:56:15,920 --> 00:56:18,080
Detective Valdez didn't give up.  

514
00:56:19,200 --> 00:56:25,360
"Jose, just listen. You know these 
people. They're trying to help you."

515
00:56:26,880 --> 00:56:36,160
Valdez tried patiently again and again. At last 
a reaction from Jose. He pulled the blanket off,  

516
00:56:36,720 --> 00:56:43,840
swung his leg back from the edge, and stood 
up. All he was wearing underneath was a green  

517
00:56:43,840 --> 00:56:49,840
surgical gown from the hospital operating 
room. The poor guy must have been freezing.

518
00:56:51,280 --> 00:56:57,840
"What can you do to help me?" shouted Jose. 
"I got a murder charge hanging over me.  

519
00:56:58,960 --> 00:57:06,880
What do I have to live for?... My head... 
I got this pain... It won't go away."

520
00:57:08,240 --> 00:57:12,320
"Speak to him, Nat," whispered Valdez.

521
00:57:12,320 --> 00:57:21,440
I stood up, trying not to look down at the drop 
below. "Jose, we've got new evidence. I can prove  

522
00:57:21,440 --> 00:57:28,160
you didn't do it." That wasn't strictly true, but 
it might encourage him to come down from the roof.

523
00:57:29,440 --> 00:57:35,200
"Then how come they've charged me with 
murder? How come?" protested Jose.

524
00:57:36,640 --> 00:57:43,120
He threw the blanket over the edge. There 
was a sudden shock of panic below until it  

525
00:57:43,120 --> 00:57:47,760
became obvious that it was the blanket 
rather than Jose that was falling.  

526
00:57:48,960 --> 00:57:55,920
Then he sat on the wall, with his head 
down. Again, he swung one leg over the edge.

527
00:57:57,280 --> 00:57:59,840
"What do you think?" I whispered to Valdez.

528
00:58:01,120 --> 00:58:07,840
"Not good, but not a disaster, I'd like 
Stella to talk to him now," she said.

529
00:58:08,480 --> 00:58:15,200
Stella's voice was cracking with emotion 
as she spoke. "Jose? Listen to me.  

530
00:58:16,160 --> 00:58:23,680
I know you didn't do it. You're not a killer. 
Something happened to you after you left that bar  

531
00:58:24,320 --> 00:58:30,160
and Nat's going to prove it. We'll get 
you off this murder charge, I promise."

532
00:58:31,840 --> 00:58:38,160
Silence. Stella appealed to him 
again. Jose responded at last.  

533
00:58:39,280 --> 00:58:45,120
"What do you have to promise with?" 
Now there was a change in his behavior.  

534
00:58:46,160 --> 00:58:55,440
Words were coming slowly as if speech involved a 
major physical and mental effort. "I... don't...  

535
00:58:56,720 --> 00:59:04,000
know... I'm... finished... My head..."

536
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:06,080
"What's happening?" asked Stella.

537
00:59:06,960 --> 00:59:13,040
"I think he's going to jump," Valdez whispered. 
"But I don't want to frighten him with any  

538
00:59:13,040 --> 00:59:20,320
sudden movements. Nat, get ready to grab 
him, but don't move until I say 'Now'."

539
00:59:22,080 --> 00:59:28,640
Jose's body began to tremble violently. He 
began to rock his body from side to side.

540
00:59:29,840 --> 00:59:35,280
"I'm... a... no... good... 
failure..." he muttered.

541
00:59:36,320 --> 00:59:41,440
"Get ready, Nat," whispered 
Valdez. "Start moving in on him."

542
00:59:42,960 --> 00:59:50,080
Jose continued muttering to himself, with his 
head lowered. Sometimes what he said made sense,  

543
00:59:50,800 --> 00:59:57,840
sometimes it was just a confused string of 
words. I crept along the roof towards him.

544
00:59:59,120 --> 01:00:03,920
"I'm... a... no... good... fail..."

545
01:00:05,280 --> 01:00:12,400
As Jose's voice trailed off into silence, the 
sideways rocking motion continued. With each  

546
01:00:12,400 --> 01:00:20,560
swing, the top part of his body hung for a moment 
over the vertical drop. Then the return swing.

547
01:00:21,920 --> 01:00:27,840
Behind me, Valdez shouted 
urgently: "This is it. NOW!"

548
01:00:28,400 --> 01:00:34,160
Jose had reached the furthest point of 
the swing. But this time he didn't return.  

549
01:00:35,040 --> 01:00:44,560
He was slipping off the edge. I made a dive for 
his foot and just managed to grab it. Jose was now  

550
01:00:44,560 --> 01:00:51,200
hanging upside down over the edge. 
I was also hanging over the edge,  

551
01:00:51,200 --> 01:00:56,640
with only my knees pressed against the 
wall preventing me from following Jose.  

552
01:00:58,080 --> 01:01:05,840
Stella and Valdez were already hanging on to me, 
but in that position, no one else could reach Jose  

553
01:01:05,840 --> 01:01:14,720
from the roof. Jose was not light and I could 
feel my grip slipping. Valdez was screaming to  

554
01:01:14,720 --> 01:01:20,720
the firefighters below: "Move it! Get that 
ladder up here before we have a fatality!"

555
01:01:22,240 --> 01:01:27,600
I concentrated all my efforts on 
keeping my arm locked around his foot.  

556
01:01:28,720 --> 01:01:38,080
Jose swung in space over the drop. I could feel 
my muscles aching and weakening. Then out of the  

557
01:01:38,080 --> 01:01:45,200
corner of my eye, I noticed the ladder swinging 
round. At the top of the ladder, there was a  

558
01:01:45,200 --> 01:01:52,720
firefighter, who took Jose's unconscious body into 
his powerful arms and swung him over his shoulder.  

559
01:01:54,080 --> 01:02:00,400
As Jose was brought down to safety, a medical team 
on the ground was waiting to take him straight to  

560
01:02:00,400 --> 01:02:07,600
the operating room. I pushed myself back from the 
edge and collapsed behind the safety of the wall.

561
01:02:09,040 --> 01:02:12,400
I opened my eyes to see Stella kneeling beside me.  

562
01:02:13,600 --> 01:02:18,160
"Nat, are you OK?" she 
asked. "You were wonderful!"

563
01:02:19,200 --> 01:02:26,960
"Thanks. I'm alright. Just let me lie here. I 
don't want to see that drop again just yet."  

564
01:02:28,560 --> 01:02:32,240
I lay there for a while, 
thinking it was good to be alive,  

565
01:02:32,240 --> 01:02:36,480
after all. I'd had quite 
enough excitement for one day.

566
01:02:38,080 --> 01:02:41,040
"Nat, you're a hero," said Valdez.

567
01:02:42,320 --> 01:02:49,280
"Well, if I'm a hero, so are you. You read 
all the signs that he was going to jump.  

568
01:02:50,240 --> 01:02:54,400
Anyway, let's get down to the operating 
room and see what's happening."

569
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:00,320
We were informed that Dr. Ericson 
was already operating on Jose.  

570
01:03:01,440 --> 01:03:08,240
The brain surgery was a delicate procedure 
which would take hours. There was also a high  

571
01:03:08,240 --> 01:03:16,320
element of risk. Jose had already put himself 
in danger by escaping from the operating room.  

572
01:03:16,320 --> 01:03:19,680
The added stress could only 
have done further damage.  

573
01:03:21,280 --> 01:03:28,640
Stella decided to stay at the hospital and wait 
for news. As I left, she was calling her mother.  

574
01:03:29,680 --> 01:03:37,200
A better option for me was home, 
food, beer, TV, and relaxation.
 
 

