01:03:54,320 --> 01:04:00,240
stayed overnight at Metropolitan Hospital. 
Her brother had come out of surgery but was  

579
01:04:00,240 --> 01:04:06,720
still unconscious. It was still too early to 
tell whether the surgery had been a success.

580
01:04:08,240 --> 01:04:13,920
I was now convinced that someone wanted 
a convenient fall guy to take the blame  

581
01:04:13,920 --> 01:04:21,200
for Romanov's murder. Maybe Jose had simply 
been unfortunate enough to be in the wrong  

582
01:04:21,200 --> 01:04:27,840
place at the wrong time. Just a harmless guy 
enjoying an evening out with his buddies.  

583
01:04:28,960 --> 01:04:35,520
Now he was facing a murder charge. The 
problem was our total lack of evidence.  

584
01:04:36,560 --> 01:04:42,720
The whole thing made me angry. But I couldn't 
allow that anger to affect my judgment.

585
01:04:44,240 --> 01:04:50,160
Meanwhile, I'd done a little research on the 
cross that Edie Tilden had seen on the body on  

586
01:04:50,160 --> 01:04:57,200
Jones Beach. It was definitely Russian - the 
design used in the Russian Orthodox Church.  

587
01:04:58,480 --> 01:05:02,240
It was likely that the letters on 
the lifeboat were also Russian.

588
01:05:03,600 --> 01:05:11,040
I now had photographs of Jose, Miguel, and 
Carlos. I'd phoned all the bars in the area  

589
01:05:11,040 --> 01:05:16,880
and had finally discovered one run by a 
baseball enthusiast - the Odessa Steps.  

590
01:05:18,000 --> 01:05:23,600
I decided it was time to take a trip to Brighton 
Beach and follow the movements of the three  

591
01:05:23,600 --> 01:05:29,680
friends on Wednesday night. There was a small 
chance I'd pick up a few pieces of evidence.

592
01:05:31,280 --> 01:05:35,040
As I was getting ready to leave, 
I had a surprise phone call.  

593
01:05:35,840 --> 01:05:39,840
Edie Tilden, the elderly 
woman I'd met at Jones Beach.

594
01:05:41,200 --> 01:05:46,160
"Mr. Marley? Edie Tilden. Remember me?" she asked.

595
01:05:47,120 --> 01:05:50,240
"It's kind of hard to forget you," I replied.

596
01:05:51,280 --> 01:05:54,000
"You're not going to believe this,  

597
01:05:54,000 --> 01:05:59,760
but I found two more bodies on the 
beach. Cold and stiff, they were!"

598
01:06:00,960 --> 01:06:05,040
I gripped the phone tightly. 
"Now don't get over-excited.  

599
01:06:05,840 --> 01:06:09,360
Just describe what you saw. Don't dramatize."

600
01:06:10,480 --> 01:06:16,320
"Well, it was early this morning. I was 
out to see what the morning high tide  

601
01:06:16,320 --> 01:06:22,400
had washed up along the shore. 
And then I found them. Two more  

602
01:06:22,400 --> 01:06:28,480
young men. About five-hundred yards east 
from where the boat was wrecked," said Edie.

603
01:06:29,600 --> 01:06:35,920
Edie went on to describe them. The two young 
men could have been anywhere in their twenties.  

604
01:06:36,880 --> 01:06:39,760
Like the other two bodies, they were very thin.  

605
01:06:40,800 --> 01:06:47,840
They were wearing cheap casual clothes: jeans, 
denim jackets, T-shirts, and running shoes.  

606
01:06:48,960 --> 01:06:54,160
Clothes worn by young men everywhere; 
nothing specific to go on here.

607
01:06:55,520 --> 01:07:01,520
"Did you notice any jewelry or 
identifying marks? Like scars?" I asked.

608
01:07:02,480 --> 01:07:05,200
"No, nothing like that," she said.

609
01:07:06,480 --> 01:07:10,880
"Thanks Edie. That's good work. 
You should have been a detective.  

610
01:07:11,840 --> 01:07:17,200
Keep on with the beachcombing. Call me anytime 
you see something suspicious, will you?"

611
01:07:18,720 --> 01:07:27,840
I was very curious. A murder in Coney Island, 
and now four bodies washed up on Jones Beach.  

612
01:07:28,960 --> 01:07:33,520
Romanov was a respected member of 
the Russian community. And it looked  

613
01:07:33,520 --> 01:07:40,400
like the four dead men found on Jones Beach 
were also Russian. Was there a connection?

614
01:07:41,760 --> 01:07:48,160
I was wondering how those boys had died. 
Drowned accidentally in a storm or what?  

615
01:07:49,600 --> 01:07:53,840
I called the Coast Guard press officer, 
who had prepared a news release.  

616
01:07:54,800 --> 01:08:01,680
He promised to email it to me immediately. As 
I put the phone down, the email came through.
 
 

617
01:08:03,440 --> 01:08:05,680
U.S. Coast Guard Group Moriches

618
01:08:06,320 --> 01:08:07,120
Press Release

619
01:08:08,240 --> 01:08:10,480
Incident at Jones Beach, Long Island

620
01:08:11,600 --> 01:08:16,320
The Coast Guard Service is currently 
investigating the wreck of a lifeboat  

621
01:08:16,320 --> 01:08:21,760
discovered on Jones Beach and also 
the discovery of four bodies nearby.  

622
01:08:22,880 --> 01:08:27,600
The victims are white, male, and 
aged between twenty and thirty.

623
01:08:28,720 --> 01:08:33,040
The wreck is being investigated as 
suspicious for the following reasons:

624
01:08:34,320 --> 01:08:36,400
No boats have been reported missing.

625
01:08:37,520 --> 01:08:40,240
No person has been reported missing at sea.

626
01:08:41,520 --> 01:08:44,000
The boat was not in seaworthy condition.

627
01:08:45,360 --> 01:08:48,400
No registration details 
are available for the boat.

628
01:08:49,680 --> 01:08:54,480
If you have any information that would 
be of assistance to the U.S. Coast Guard,  

629
01:08:54,480 --> 01:09:02,640
please contact Commander J. Lockhart, U.S. Coast 
Guard Station Moriches, Long Island, New York.

630
01:09:03,920 --> 01:09:11,840
I printed out the email and put it aside to read 
again later. It was time to go Brighton Beach  

631
01:09:11,840 --> 01:09:15,440
and pay a visit to the bar 
where Jose had fallen asleep.  

632
01:09:16,800 --> 01:09:23,280
I took an express Q train from the 42nd Street 
subway station. As the train made its way through  

633
01:09:23,280 --> 01:09:30,160
the suburbs of Brooklyn, I glanced through the 
Daily News. Nothing more on the Romanov story.

634
01:09:31,520 --> 01:09:37,520
I got out at the Brighton Beach subway station 
and started working my way along the avenue,  

635
01:09:37,520 --> 01:09:42,480
inquiring at bars whether Jose and his 
buddies might have been drinking there.  

636
01:09:43,600 --> 01:09:50,160
It was just before noon so the bars were 
still quiet. A couple of bartenders vaguely  

637
01:09:50,160 --> 01:09:54,720
recognized the photographs but couldn't 
provide me with anything useful.

638
01:09:56,400 --> 01:10:03,760
I finally arrived at the Odessa Steps. Inside, 
the walls were covered with baseball souvenirs:  

639
01:10:04,640 --> 01:10:10,560
picture after picture of the famous Brooklyn 
Dodgers teams who dominated the American  

640
01:10:10,560 --> 01:10:18,560
baseball scene in the 1940s and 50s. I ordered 
a beer and sat down to take in the atmosphere.  

641
01:10:19,680 --> 01:10:25,280
The lunchtime crowd was arriving and the bar 
was becoming noisy with Russian conversation.  

642
01:10:26,800 --> 01:10:32,800
At the next table, one of the staff had a 
collection of tools on the table and also,  

643
01:10:32,800 --> 01:10:38,240
a beautiful antique baseball bat. He 
was preparing to put it on the wall.

644
01:10:39,600 --> 01:10:45,440
"Excuse me," I said. "I'm interested 
in the bat. I bet it has a history.  

645
01:10:46,320 --> 01:10:49,040
Something new for the baseball exhibition, huh?"

646
01:10:50,320 --> 01:10:57,920
"This bat, mister, was used in the 
final game of the 1955 World Series,"  

647
01:10:57,920 --> 01:11:03,920
proudly replied the bartender, "when the 
Brooklyn Dodgers beat the New York Yankees.  

648
01:11:04,720 --> 01:11:09,040
It's my boss's favorite piece. 
He paid a fortune for it."

649
01:11:10,160 --> 01:11:13,520
"At today's prices, I'm sure he did," I said.

650
01:11:14,640 --> 01:11:20,400
"Well, that was back in the 1980s, 
so it isn't a new piece. We've had  

651
01:11:20,400 --> 01:11:25,760
it up here in the bar for years. 
You're not going to believe this,  

652
01:11:25,760 --> 01:11:31,440
but Wednesday night last week, 
some joker pulled it off the wall."

653
01:11:32,800 --> 01:11:40,080
"No kidding! Whoever it was would've been 
lucky to get out of here alive," I commented.

654
01:11:40,080 --> 01:11:41,920
"I guess so," he said.

655
01:11:43,200 --> 01:11:48,960
I showed him my investigator's license, and 
also the photos of Jose and his buddies.

656
01:11:50,240 --> 01:11:54,800
"Did you happen to see these three 
guys in here on Wednesday?" I asked.

657
01:11:55,920 --> 01:12:02,160
He immediately pointed at Jose's picture. 
"Hey, that's the guy who grabbed the bat!"

658
01:12:03,360 --> 01:12:04,400
"What time was this?"

659
01:12:05,440 --> 01:12:12,880
"Had to be nine o'clock. I remember because it 
was just before my break," the bartender replied.

660
01:12:14,160 --> 01:12:17,440
"What happened to this guy 
after he tried to take the bat?"

661
01:12:18,960 --> 01:12:26,800
So far the bartender had been talkative. Now he 
looked nervous and started to hesitate. "Er...  

662
01:12:27,360 --> 01:12:35,840
I must have been on my break. Look, why don't you 
ask my colleague behind the bar. He'll remember."

663
01:12:37,600 --> 01:12:44,400
The conversation with the other bartender followed 
the same pattern. His memory was perfectly clear  

664
01:12:44,960 --> 01:12:47,360
up to the point when Jose took the bat.  

665
01:12:48,400 --> 01:12:55,840
Mysteriously, they both suffered from total memory 
loss after that. Were they hiding something?  

666
01:12:56,640 --> 01:13:04,480
Or were they scared of something? I was certain 
about one thing. If a stranger walked into this  

667
01:13:04,480 --> 01:13:11,200
bar and attempted to steal one of their sports 
treasures, they'd be lucky to get away unharmed.  

668
01:13:12,320 --> 01:13:17,840
Was it possible Jose received those 
throat and head injuries in the bar?

669
01:13:18,480 --> 01:13:23,760
I didn't think I was going to find out anything 
more, but at least I had made some progress.  

670
01:13:24,800 --> 01:13:32,240
Jose and his buddies had definitely 
been in the bar. I had a time, 9:00 PM,  

671
01:13:32,240 --> 01:13:40,560
when Jose must have woken up, and in his confused 
state made a grab for the bat. But why wouldn't  

672
01:13:40,560 --> 01:13:48,160
the bartenders reveal anything more? I stayed 
at the bar and ordered a roast beef sandwich  

673
01:13:48,160 --> 01:13:55,280
and fries. While I was waiting for the food, I 
made a call to Stella at Metropolitan hospital.  

674
01:13:56,240 --> 01:14:03,280
Jose was still in intensive care, slipping 
into a coma, a state of deep unconsciousness.

675
01:14:04,800 --> 01:14:11,360
"Nat," said Stella. "My mom's going to take 
over for me at the hospital. I'll be going  

676
01:14:11,360 --> 01:14:18,640
home soon to get some sleep. I'm just exhausted. 
But I'll be at the office first thing tomorrow."

677
01:14:20,000 --> 01:14:24,080
"You know you don't have to if you 
want to keep your mom company," I said.

678
01:14:25,280 --> 01:14:32,080
"Nat, I'm depending on you to clear Jose's name 
and prove his innocence. Let's get on with this  

679
01:14:32,080 --> 01:14:36,080
investigation. I'm going to 
be right there with you."
 
 

680
01:14:39,600 --> 01:14:40,400
CHAPTER SEVEN

681
01:14:41,200 --> 01:14:41,840
Evidence

682
01:14:43,840 --> 01:14:51,360
Early Tuesday morning, on Main Street in Queens, 
the weather was just awful. It was pouring,  

683
01:14:51,920 --> 01:14:59,200
with fat raindrops bouncing off the sidewalks. Car 
headlights were reflecting off the road surface,  

684
01:14:59,840 --> 01:15:07,200
in places now inches deep in water. 
I splashed along the sidewalk. My hat  

685
01:15:07,200 --> 01:15:11,440
and coat were soaking wet by the 
time I got to the subway station.

686
01:15:13,040 --> 01:15:19,760
At East 43rd Street, it all seemed like a 
normal day. Stella was already at her desk  

687
01:15:20,320 --> 01:15:26,000
going through the morning mail. She 
gave me her usual bright 'Hi, Nat.'  

688
01:15:27,040 --> 01:15:34,640
But underneath that cheerful exterior, I knew 
she was deeply worried. As soon as I'd woken up,  

689
01:15:35,200 --> 01:15:42,480
I'd phoned the hospital to get an update on 
Jose's condition. I was simply told: 'No change'.

690
01:15:44,000 --> 01:15:51,280
The investigation into Jose's evening at Brighton 
Beach had made little progress. I'd also had a  

691
01:15:51,280 --> 01:15:58,480
call from Lena Rosenthal. Oldenberg had given 
all the relevant police information to Lena,  

692
01:15:58,480 --> 01:16:03,200
our lawyer. This included the 
autopsy report on Romanov.  

693
01:16:04,400 --> 01:16:08,080
We had arranged a midmorning 
meeting at East 43rd Street.

694
01:16:09,600 --> 01:16:16,160
Over breakfast, I did some thinking. I 
recalled the basic points of police procedure  

695
01:16:16,160 --> 01:16:19,840
which I'd been taught years 
ago at the NYPD Academy.  

696
01:16:21,200 --> 01:16:31,120
In every investigation, always establish M.O.M., 
which stands for 'Motive, Opportunity, and Means.'  

697
01:16:32,560 --> 01:16:41,040
Motive - why did the suspect commit the crime? 
Opportunity - did the suspect have the chance to  

698
01:16:41,040 --> 01:16:49,520
carry out the crime? Means - did the suspect 
have the weapon to carry out the crime? But  

699
01:16:49,520 --> 01:16:56,480
when you applied this system to Jose nothing 
seemed to make sense. There's nothing out of  

700
01:16:56,480 --> 01:17:03,760
the ordinary in a guy having too many drinks 
and waking up in a strange bar. But how and  

701
01:17:03,760 --> 01:17:10,640
why could he suddenly come into the possession 
of a handgun, steal a car, and commit murder?

702
01:17:12,320 --> 01:17:18,320
Later that morning, Lena was going through some of 
the details of Romanov's autopsy report with me.

703
01:17:19,600 --> 01:17:28,240
"What worries me Nat, is timing," she began. "We 
know that Jose probably left the Odessa Steps  

704
01:17:28,240 --> 01:17:32,720
at or around nine o'clock. 
According to this report,  

705
01:17:33,280 --> 01:17:40,160
Romanov's time of death was somewhere 
between 8:45 and 9:45 the same evening.  

706
01:17:41,280 --> 01:17:46,960
Now, for a drunk who'd just woken up, Jose 
would have to have been one fast mover."

707
01:17:48,000 --> 01:17:49,600
"Agreed," I said.

708
01:17:50,640 --> 01:17:58,560
"There's absolutely nothing to show how or where 
he came across Romanov," Lena continued. "Did  

709
01:17:58,560 --> 01:18:06,240
he just walk out into the street, wave a car to 
stop, and then rob and brutally murder the driver?  

710
01:18:07,360 --> 01:18:13,600
As I see it, there's no logic here. No 
supporting evidence apart from the forensics."

711
01:18:14,800 --> 01:18:16,320
"Anything more in the reports?"

712
01:18:17,440 --> 01:18:24,480
"Cause of death, a gunshot to the head at 
close range. Romanov was on the ground when  

713
01:18:24,480 --> 01:18:31,280
he was killed. According to the report, 
there was bruising on his upper arms  

714
01:18:31,280 --> 01:18:37,120
which could indicate the killer was standing 
on his arms when the fatal shot was fired."

715
01:18:38,560 --> 01:18:42,480
Stella, who had been making some 
notes, suddenly interrupted.

716
01:18:43,440 --> 01:18:50,080
"Ms. Rosenthal, I need to get something clear. The 
fingerprints that were found on the gun barrel.  

717
01:18:51,120 --> 01:18:53,840
Right-hand or left-hand prints?"

718
01:18:54,400 --> 01:18:58,320
"All right-hand prints, according 
to the report," Lena replied.

719
01:18:59,600 --> 01:19:03,120
Stella said nothing but just 
looked down at the notepad.

720
01:19:04,480 --> 01:19:07,840
"Stella, is Jose right-handed?" I asked.

721
01:19:09,040 --> 01:19:12,000
Stella nodded. Another setback.  

722
01:19:13,120 --> 01:19:19,600
If only Jose was lefthanded. Another 
possible line of investigation closed.

723
01:19:21,280 --> 01:19:26,640
Oldenberg had not followed official 
procedure after Dr. Ericson had reported  

724
01:19:26,640 --> 01:19:33,280
the bruises on Jose's neck. With some 
minor blackmail, I could ask a favor.  

725
01:19:34,400 --> 01:19:40,800
I thought I might have a talk with Oldenberg. 
I knew a subject that would hold his attention:  

726
01:19:41,680 --> 01:19:47,200
baseball. His mind is an 
encyclopedia of baseball history.

727
01:19:48,480 --> 01:19:54,960
"Oldenberg? It's Marley. Just called 
to tell you I've been admiring a bat  

728
01:19:54,960 --> 01:20:01,120
used by the Brooklyn Dodgers in the 
final game of the 1955 World Series."

729
01:20:02,400 --> 01:20:08,640
There was a low whistle of surprise from 
Oldenberg. I knew I had his full attention.

730
01:20:09,920 --> 01:20:16,320
"It's a valuable piece of baseball history," I 
continued, "and you can see it for yourself at the  

731
01:20:16,320 --> 01:20:24,400
Odessa Steps bar on Brighton Beach. They've got a 
whole museum of baseball stuff around the walls.  

732
01:20:25,520 --> 01:20:30,400
But last Wednesday night, some 
guy pulled this bat off the wall."

733
01:20:31,440 --> 01:20:35,760
"Hey, that would be terrible. 
That guy would be lucky to..."

734
01:20:36,560 --> 01:20:42,800
"Get out of the place in one piece?" I suggested. 
"That's what people at the bar told me.  

735
01:20:43,840 --> 01:20:52,480
And the guy is the accused, Jose De La Cruz. 
But he got out of the bar somehow. And then  

736
01:20:52,480 --> 01:20:59,120
look what happened to him. Kind of strange, 
don't you think? Especially when the bar  

737
01:20:59,120 --> 01:21:05,200
staff went suspiciously quiet when I asked 
what happened after Jose grabbed the bat."

738
01:21:06,400 --> 01:21:11,760
"I don't know what to say, Marley. This 
information might have an effect on the case."

739
01:21:12,960 --> 01:21:21,120
"Think about it. Now," I continued, "it's come to 
my attention that medical staff at Metropolitan  

740
01:21:21,120 --> 01:21:26,080
reported bruising on De La Cruz's neck, 
which couldn't have been the result of  

741
01:21:26,080 --> 01:21:31,760
the car crash. But you didn't order 
a medical examination of my client."

742
01:21:32,960 --> 01:21:35,920
"How did you know about that?" demanded Oldenberg.

743
01:21:36,960 --> 01:21:43,760
"Just doing my job," I replied calmly. 
"I have my contacts. I'm prepared to  

744
01:21:43,760 --> 01:21:49,440
ignore this failure to follow official 
procedure if you do me a little favor.  

745
01:21:50,400 --> 01:21:57,040
I need an official introduction from the 
NYPD to Lockhart, Commander of the Coast  

746
01:21:57,040 --> 01:22:01,440
Guard Group in Moriches. That's 
the Long Island South section."

747
01:22:02,800 --> 01:22:04,720
"What's this all about, Marley?"

748
01:22:05,760 --> 01:22:09,840
"Let's just say another line of inquiry."

749
01:22:10,560 --> 01:22:17,280
One o'clock. It had been a busy morning 
and I could hear a cold beer calling my  

750
01:22:17,280 --> 01:22:23,840
name from McFadden's Bar. McFadden's Bar is 
just a block across town from the office,  

751
01:22:24,560 --> 01:22:29,280
on Second Avenue, a favorite watering 
hole for New York journalists.  

752
01:22:30,480 --> 01:22:38,080
I phoned the bar to check whether Ed Winchester 
was there. Ed's an old friend and a wonderful  

753
01:22:38,080 --> 01:22:44,160
source of information. He'd been chief 
crime reporter for the Daily News for years,  

754
01:22:44,720 --> 01:22:52,000
and still did some part-time work for the 
paper, though he was now officially retired.

755
01:22:52,000 --> 01:22:56,400
No sooner had I entered the bar 
than I heard my name being called.  

756
01:22:57,280 --> 01:23:05,920
A tall elderly guy with silver hair and a 
deeply-lined face was waving an empty glass at me.

757
01:23:05,920 --> 01:23:08,960
"Nat, perfect timing!" Ed said.

758
01:23:10,080 --> 01:23:13,600
"That must mean your glass 
needs refilling," I replied.

759
01:23:14,960 --> 01:23:22,000
I took the beers over to an empty table and went 
though all the recent events with Ed: Romanov's  

760
01:23:22,000 --> 01:23:29,760
death, Jose's night out at Brighton Beach, the 
wrecked lifeboat, and the bodies on Jones Beach.

761
01:23:31,040 --> 01:23:37,840
"You see, Ed, there seem to be Russian 
connections everywhere. I was just curious  

762
01:23:37,840 --> 01:23:42,080
whether you'd heard anything about 
crime among the Russian community."

763
01:23:43,440 --> 01:23:50,560
"Money laundering is the big one," he replied. 
"In international terms, the Russian ruble is  

764
01:23:50,560 --> 01:23:57,920
seen as little more than toy money. So much of the 
real business of crime is done in hard currency,  

765
01:23:58,480 --> 01:24:04,240
in U.S. dollars. A lot of illegal 
dollars from that black economy are  

766
01:24:04,240 --> 01:24:11,600
probably coming in to the U.S.A. from Russia. 
The problem then is how to integrate that money  

767
01:24:11,600 --> 01:24:15,840
into the legal economy here 
without attracting attention."

768
01:24:16,800 --> 01:24:20,400
I'd heard about money laundering. Anybody running  

769
01:24:20,400 --> 01:24:26,960
organized crime operations like drugs or 
illegal gambling receives huge amounts of cash.  

770
01:24:27,920 --> 01:24:34,240
Thus the need for your friendly neighborhood 
money launderer to clean the dirty money  

771
01:24:34,240 --> 01:24:40,240
by transferring it through a network of bank 
accounts until nobody can find where it came from.  

772
01:24:41,440 --> 01:24:47,040
Once it reappears at the other end of 
the process, the money's clean and legal.

773
01:24:48,480 --> 01:24:54,160
Ed called the crime desk to see if they knew 
of any money laundering activity in the Russian  

774
01:24:54,160 --> 01:25:00,960
community. He listened carefully for a couple of 
minutes, then turned to me with a broad smile.

775
01:25:02,400 --> 01:25:10,000
"There's a guy by the name of Victor Kamenev" he 
said. "It seems he was depositing regular amounts  

776
01:25:10,000 --> 01:25:17,360
of cash, up to ten thousand dollars at a time, 
in a variety of banks around lower Manhattan.  

777
01:25:18,240 --> 01:25:24,800
He's got a business - Kamenev Finance. Of 
course, there was the usual gossip at the  

778
01:25:24,800 --> 01:25:31,840
crime desk as to whether he was laundering money 
for the Russian Mafia but no concrete evidence."

779
01:25:33,360 --> 01:25:41,360
Ed had delivered the goods again, and cheap 
at the price of a beer. Another Russian name -  

780
01:25:41,360 --> 01:25:47,600
but was there any possible connection between 
Romanov's death and the wreck on Jones Beach?  

781
01:25:49,120 --> 01:25:54,560
I walked across town to First Avenue and 
wandered through the United Nations Plaza  

782
01:25:54,560 --> 01:26:01,440
over to the East River. Walking time is 
thinking time so I just ignored the rain.  

783
01:26:02,720 --> 01:26:10,160
I needed a way to gain access to the Russian 
community. Alexei Romanov's widow could be our  

784
01:26:10,160 --> 01:26:17,280
entry key. But under the circumstances, we might 
have to be a little economical with the truth.

785
01:26:18,960 --> 01:26:24,640
The initial approach to Mrs. Romanov 
would need tact and sensitivity - more  

786
01:26:24,640 --> 01:26:31,520
Stella's specialty than mine. Back at the 
office, after describing the plan to Stella,  

787
01:26:32,160 --> 01:26:39,040
she made that all-important call. Her 
telephone manner was, as always, perfect.

788
01:26:40,320 --> 01:26:46,160
"Mrs. Romanov? I'm very sorry to 
disturb you at this extremely sad time.  

789
01:26:47,040 --> 01:26:52,080
I'm Stella Delgado. My employer, Mr. Nat Marley,  

790
01:26:52,080 --> 01:26:56,960
is investigating a matter which is of 
deep concern to the Russian community..."

791
01:26:58,480 --> 01:27:04,400
After Stella had completed the call, we had 
an appointment for the following afternoon.
 
 

792
01:27:08,160 --> 01:27:08,880
CHAPTER EIGHT

793
01:27:09,680 --> 01:27:10,800
Mrs. Romanov

794
01:27:12,880 --> 01:27:18,080
It was one of those March mornings when 
the weather still hadn't made up its mind  

795
01:27:18,080 --> 01:27:25,520
if it's the depth of winter or the beginning of 
spring. An icy wind was cutting across Manhattan.  

796
01:27:26,400 --> 01:27:30,000
A few snowflakes were falling 
from the heavy, gray clouds.  

797
01:27:31,200 --> 01:27:36,800
I'd arranged to meet Stella at Metropolitan 
Hospital, where she'd been at Jose's bedside  

798
01:27:36,800 --> 01:27:43,120
with her mom. Stella was waiting outside 
the main entrance, shivering with cold.

799
01:27:44,320 --> 01:27:47,760
"You'll catch your death of 
cold out here, Stella," I said.

800
01:27:48,880 --> 01:27:53,680
"I prefer it out here. Right now 
I've had enough of hospitals.  

801
01:27:54,560 --> 01:28:03,120
I've just been with Jose for an hour. There's 
no change. Still in a deep coma. Just the same  

802
01:28:03,120 --> 01:28:09,840
as before. At least the police are being more 
relaxed about access now that he's unconscious."

803
01:28:11,120 --> 01:28:14,560
"I'd like to see him anyway 
now that I'm here," I said.

804
01:28:16,000 --> 01:28:23,280
We made our way up to Jose's room. As usual, 
the police guard was on duty outside the room.  

805
01:28:24,480 --> 01:28:30,240
Through the window, I could see Stella's mom at 
the bedside, talking to the unconscious Jose.

806
01:28:31,760 --> 01:28:38,400
"See that, Nat? Mom spends hour after 
hour chatting to him. She's convinced  

807
01:28:38,400 --> 01:28:43,200
she's getting through to him. But I 
haven't noticed any kind of response."

808
01:28:44,480 --> 01:28:46,800
"Let's hope it does some good," I said.

809
01:28:48,240 --> 01:28:52,880
I didn't feel it was appropriate 
to enter the room. Jose was with  

810
01:28:52,880 --> 01:28:58,800
his family. I knew that the unconscious 
brain can still be active and functioning.  

811
01:28:59,760 --> 01:29:02,240
I just hoped he was receiving something,  

812
01:29:02,960 --> 01:29:08,400
something that might get though whatever block 
was keeping him from regaining consciousness.

813
01:29:09,920 --> 01:29:15,680
Yesterday, Oldenberg had emailed me a 
letter of introduction to a Commander  

814
01:29:15,680 --> 01:29:20,880
Lockhart of the U.S. Coast Guard, who was 
based at the Moriches Coast Guard Station.  

815
01:29:22,000 --> 01:29:26,320
I'd already made an appointment to talk 
to him about the Jones Beach wreck.  

816
01:29:27,840 --> 01:29:33,760
The wrecked lifeboat was now being stored at 
Jones Beach Coast Guard Station, and I had  

817
01:29:33,760 --> 01:29:41,840
arranged to meet Lockhart there. I was curious to 
examine it and prove any new Russian connections.  

818
01:29:43,280 --> 01:29:50,160
As far as this investigation was concerned, 
it was all a very long shot. It could easily  

819
01:29:50,160 --> 01:29:55,440
be a pointless visit. But I felt we 
should be doing something for Jose.

820
01:29:57,200 --> 01:30:04,960
The subway was clear of the worst of the rush hour 
crowds. As the number four train sped downtown  

821
01:30:04,960 --> 01:30:11,280
toward midtown Manhattan, I thought over what I 
knew about Jose's night out in Brighton Beach.  

822
01:30:12,560 --> 01:30:17,680
If only he would regain consciousness, 
then he might recall something relevant.

823
01:30:19,200 --> 01:30:24,800
From 51st Street, an E train took 
us west across town to Penn Station,  

824
01:30:25,440 --> 01:30:32,640
where we took a Long Island Rail Road train to 
Freeport. A forty-minute journey, but quicker and  

825
01:30:32,640 --> 01:30:40,960
cheaper than any cab. As the train made its way 
through the suburbs of Queens, I noticed Stella  

826
01:30:40,960 --> 01:30:47,840
biting her lip. I know that little habit 
of hers; it means something is on her mind.

827
01:30:49,520 --> 01:30:51,680
"Are you OK, Stella?" I asked.

828
01:30:52,640 --> 01:31:01,360
"This past week, Nat, has been a total nightmare. 
I'm tense and anxious all the time. We seem to  

829
01:31:01,360 --> 01:31:08,400
be getting nowhere fast. I know it's not your 
fault, you're doing everything you possibly can,  

830
01:31:09,360 --> 01:31:14,240
but there are times when I feel like 
tearing my hair out and screaming."

831
01:31:15,680 --> 01:31:23,920
"Don't give up hope, Stella," I said. "I won't let 
Jose down, believe me. I'm positive the evidence  

832
01:31:23,920 --> 01:31:31,760
is out there. The pressure's getting me down too. 
If this was an ordinary, everyday investigation,  

833
01:31:32,400 --> 01:31:39,200
I'd be able to walk away from it and put it right 
out of my mind. But it's there with me all the  

834
01:31:39,200 --> 01:31:47,200
time. If I wake up in the middle of the night, I'm 
thinking about it. We'll crack this case somehow."

835
01:31:49,040 --> 01:31:53,200
We took a cab from Freeport to the 
Jones Beach Coast Guard Station,  

836
01:31:53,840 --> 01:32:00,400
where we were welcomed by the officer responsible 
for Long Island South, Commander Lockhart,  

837
01:32:00,400 --> 01:32:03,440
a tall, fit-looking man in his fifties.

838
01:32:04,640 --> 01:32:10,080
"Pleased to meet you, Mr. Marley," said 
Lockhart, shaking my hand with a firm grip.  

839
01:32:11,120 --> 01:32:15,040
"Captain Oldenberg asked me to give 
you every possible assistance."

840
01:32:16,320 --> 01:32:23,440
"Thanks," I said. "This is my assistant, 
Stella Delgado. We're working on a case  

841
01:32:23,440 --> 01:32:27,760
that just might have a connection with 
the recent incident on Jones Beach.  

842
01:32:28,960 --> 01:32:34,240
As you know, we'd like to see that wrecked 
lifeboat which was recovered," I replied.

843
01:32:35,680 --> 01:32:41,760
Lockhart took us out to a workshop 
alongside the Coast Guard building. Inside  

844
01:32:41,760 --> 01:32:48,320
was part of what had once been a well-built 
boat. The paint was peeling off it.  

845
01:32:49,360 --> 01:32:53,840
Some clean fresh wood was visible 
where the boat had split in two.  

846
01:32:55,040 --> 01:33:00,960
At the back of the boat were the faded 
letters. They did look like Russian letters.

847
01:33:02,480 --> 01:33:07,840
Lockhart took a screwdriver from a workbench 
and pointed at a section of the boat.

848
01:33:08,560 --> 01:33:14,960
"I'd like to demonstrate to you just how poor 
the condition of this boat is," he announced.

849
01:33:16,080 --> 01:33:19,280
He drove the blade of the 
screwdriver into the wood.  

850
01:33:20,160 --> 01:33:25,200
It went through with little effort. 
The wood was completely rotten.

851
01:33:26,720 --> 01:33:33,680
Stella gasped. "Those poor guys!" she 
exclaimed. "They wouldn't have had a chance."

852
01:33:34,960 --> 01:33:38,560
"This boat was no more than a floating grave,"  

853
01:33:38,560 --> 01:33:42,480
Lockhart continued. "It's 
completely falling apart."

854
01:33:43,760 --> 01:33:47,760
"What about the four guys who were 
found on Jones Beach?" I asked.

855
01:33:48,880 --> 01:33:51,760
"I have the full autopsy details in my  

856
01:33:51,760 --> 01:33:55,840
office. Shall we go there and 
I'll show you?" he suggested.

857
01:33:57,280 --> 01:34:01,600
Inside his office, Lockhart sorted 
through a pile of documents.

858
01:34:02,800 --> 01:34:10,080
"Here we are. Cause of death: exposure and 
drowning. They must have floated for as  

859
01:34:10,080 --> 01:34:14,480
long as they could. Maybe holding 
on to what was left of the boat.  

860
01:34:15,360 --> 01:34:21,040
But the chance of survival in those temperatures 
would have been very slight," he said.

861
01:34:22,080 --> 01:34:26,400
"Was there any form of identification 
on the bodies?" asked Stella.

862
01:34:27,440 --> 01:34:33,360
"All that was found were some Russian labels 
on their clothes, and a Russian Orthodox cross.  

863
01:34:34,240 --> 01:34:37,040
But otherwise, we've no identification.  

864
01:34:38,000 --> 01:34:42,720
We're running a check with the Russian 
authorities, but these things take time."

865
01:34:43,920 --> 01:34:49,280
"Off the record, what do you think 
really happened to these guys?" I asked.

866
01:34:50,400 --> 01:34:58,880
"Our guess is an illegal immigration operation," 
Lockhart began. "They probably paid a huge amount  

867
01:34:58,880 --> 01:35:06,640
of money for the privilege of being smuggled 
from Russia into the U.S.A. In cases like these,  

868
01:35:06,640 --> 01:35:13,840
another bigger boat would be involved, probably 
a small fishing boat. They remain offshore,  

869
01:35:14,480 --> 01:35:17,440
then transfer the immigrants into smaller boats."

870
01:35:18,720 --> 01:35:24,160
"Are you talking about occasional incidents 
or regular shipments of immigrants?" I asked.

871
01:35:25,280 --> 01:35:32,400
"We suspect regular traffic. We've had a 
number of reports of suspicious activity from  

872
01:35:32,400 --> 01:35:38,880
routine Coast Guard patrols. The Coast Guard 
has carried out a number of search and seizure  

873
01:35:38,880 --> 01:35:45,680
operations at sea, but our resources are 
limited. For every illegal immigrant we  

874
01:35:45,680 --> 01:35:53,200
seize, there could be others slipping through the 
net. Of course, we question the ones we catch,  

875
01:35:53,200 --> 01:35:59,440
but never learn anything really useful, like 
names of the people behind the operation."

876
01:36:00,960 --> 01:36:10,080
"Thanks," I said. "This has been very useful. If 
I discover anything relevant, I'll let you know."

877
01:36:10,080 --> 01:36:17,040
"Mr. Marley, whoever put any people into 
that boat might as well have been holding a  

878
01:36:17,040 --> 01:36:23,840
gun to their heads," said Lockhart. "You 
realize there could still be more bodies?  

879
01:36:24,720 --> 01:36:27,840
It could take time before they're 
all washed onto the beach."

880
01:36:29,360 --> 01:36:35,680
From Jones Beach, we took a cab to Brighton 
Beach. The heavy clouds had begun to lift  

881
01:36:35,680 --> 01:36:39,520
slightly and the occasional ray 
of sunshine was breaking through.  

882
01:36:40,960 --> 01:36:47,120
Our next appointment - with Alexei Romanov's 
widow - had to be handled very delicately.

883
01:36:48,640 --> 01:36:52,960
The Romanov house was situated in a 
wealthy neighborhood of Brighton Beach,  

884
01:36:53,520 --> 01:36:58,080
off Shore Boulevard. Large houses with well-cared  

885
01:36:58,080 --> 01:37:03,440
for gardens. None of the trees had 
been optimistic enough to think about  

886
01:37:03,440 --> 01:37:08,800
bursting into leaf yet. The temperature 
couldn't have been much above freezing.  

887
01:37:10,480 --> 01:37:16,320
The door was answered by a maid who took our 
names and left us waiting in the entrance hall.

888
01:37:17,760 --> 01:37:23,120
Soon, she returned and led us into 
an elegantly furnished dining room.  

889
01:37:24,480 --> 01:37:33,600
Mrs. Romanov then entered - a tall gray-haired 
woman wearing a black dress with a simple gold pin  

890
01:37:33,600 --> 01:37:40,480
fastened at her throat. In her face, you could see 
the grief that she must have been going through.

891
01:37:42,080 --> 01:37:47,840
"Ms. Delgado and Mr. Marley. 
Welcome. Do sit down," she said.

892
01:37:48,480 --> 01:37:54,960
"We realize that this is not an appropriate 
time to visit," began Stella. "We're aware  

893
01:37:54,960 --> 01:37:59,440
of the good work your late husband did 
with newly arrived Russian immigrants,  

894
01:38:00,080 --> 01:38:02,960
and we'd like to offer our deepest sympathies."

895
01:38:04,160 --> 01:38:07,200
"Thank you. You're most kind," she said.

896
01:38:08,480 --> 01:38:13,600
"Our visit concerns Russian immigrants 
who may have been attempting to enter  

897
01:38:13,600 --> 01:38:20,480
the country illegally. You may have heard about 
the bodies found on Jones Beach?" asked Stella.

898
01:38:21,760 --> 01:38:23,280
Mrs. Romanov nodded.

899
01:38:24,480 --> 01:38:30,960
"They were probably young Russian men," Stella 
continued. "The boat they were sailing in  

900
01:38:30,960 --> 01:38:38,480
was in a completely unseaworthy condition. Whoever 
was behind this immigrant smuggling operation  

901
01:38:38,480 --> 01:38:41,200
had surely sent these boys to their deaths."

902
01:38:42,880 --> 01:38:49,680
Mrs. Romanov frowned. I could see we had 
her attention. "But this is dreadful!  

903
01:38:50,400 --> 01:38:53,760
Can I be of any assistance?" asked Mrs. Romanov.  

904
01:38:54,880 --> 01:39:01,360
"Poor Alexei would have moved heaven and earth 
to bring the people responsible to justice."

905
01:39:02,880 --> 01:39:05,680
I judged it was the right time to make my move.

906
01:39:07,040 --> 01:39:11,600
"I realize that this is not a suitable 
time to ask this question, ma'am,"  

907
01:39:11,600 --> 01:39:16,720
I said. "We know your husband was active 
with the Immigrant Welfare Society.  

908
01:39:17,680 --> 01:39:23,840
Could he possibly have made any enemies 
in the Russian community? You see, there  

909
01:39:23,840 --> 01:39:30,000
could be some connection between your husband's 
death and these poor boys found on Jones beach."

910
01:39:31,760 --> 01:39:36,880
I really couldn't be absolutely 
sure of my facts here, but again,  

911
01:39:36,880 --> 01:39:42,560
there was no harm in taking a chance if we were 
going to make any progress with Jose's case.

912
01:39:43,920 --> 01:39:50,800
"The police have already asked me all 
about..." began Mrs. Romanov. She then paused  

913
01:39:50,800 --> 01:39:58,800
and gave me a hard stare. "I don't think you're 
being completely truthful with me, Mr. Marley.  

914
01:39:59,680 --> 01:40:02,240
What is the real reason for your visit?"

915
01:40:03,680 --> 01:40:07,920
It was time to put all our cards on the table.

916
01:40:07,920 --> 01:40:17,280
"Mrs. Romanov, I apologize. Yes, I have been 
less than honest. I am a private investigator  

917
01:40:17,280 --> 01:40:24,800
representing my client, Jose De La Cruz, who, 
as you know, has been charged with the murder  

918
01:40:24,800 --> 01:40:31,840
of your late husband. I do not believe that your 
husband was the victim of a simple street crime.  

919
01:40:32,800 --> 01:40:38,000
I suspect your husband had discovered 
something that put his life in danger."

920
01:40:39,680 --> 01:40:44,880
Mrs. Romanov's face grew pale. 
She sat silently and still  

921
01:40:44,880 --> 01:40:51,280
as I continued. "We also have to admit 
that our interest in this case is personal.  

922
01:40:52,160 --> 01:40:57,040
Our client, Jose De La Cruz is 
Ms. Delgado's younger brother."

923
01:40:58,640 --> 01:41:01,120
Stella turned to face Mrs. Romanov.

924
01:41:02,240 --> 01:41:08,960
"Believe me, Mrs. Romanov, this is 
difficult for me too. As God is my witness,  

925
01:41:09,520 --> 01:41:14,080
my brother is not a killer. 
Just a gentle, harmless,  

926
01:41:14,080 --> 01:41:19,840
ordinary guy who must've been in the wrong 
place at the wrong time," said Stella.

927
01:41:21,040 --> 01:41:29,920
I continued, "As far as the NYPD are concerned, 
they've found their killer, but I'm not convinced.  

928
01:41:30,880 --> 01:41:34,480
I am asking for your help 
in finding your husband's  

929
01:41:34,480 --> 01:41:39,840
real killer or killers. I can't 
be more honest than that."
 
 

930
01:41:43,360 --> 01:41:44,160
CHAPTER NINE

931
01:41:44,160 --> 01:41:48,560
Victor Kamenev

932
01:41:48,560 --> 01:41:53,920
Mrs. Romanov stood up and stared out the 
window for a moment before speaking again.

933
01:41:55,200 --> 01:42:00,560
"Mr. Marley, Ms. Delgado," she 
said. "I believe you are sincere.  

934
01:42:01,360 --> 01:42:04,080
You may count on my cooperation and support."

935
01:42:05,680 --> 01:42:07,680
Stella looked at me and smiled.

936
01:42:08,720 --> 01:42:14,880
Mrs. Romanov continued: "You appreciate 
this is a very difficult time for me.  

937
01:42:15,600 --> 01:42:20,800
But I'll do my best. There's something 
quite weird about the events of last week.  

938
01:42:22,000 --> 01:42:27,840
I've had this feeling that the police have not 
made every effort to investigate the case fully.  

939
01:42:29,040 --> 01:42:36,960
Alexei was well respected for all his community 
work. He had a fine reputation. He made friends  

940
01:42:36,960 --> 01:42:42,880
rather than enemies. I think of all the 
people he's helped to settle here and become  

941
01:42:42,880 --> 01:42:49,280
good American citizens, and I'm not aware of 
anyone who could have anything against him."

942
01:42:50,560 --> 01:42:57,920
"Did he ever mention any names? Any little remarks 
he made about people?" I asked. "Take your time."

943
01:42:59,200 --> 01:43:05,040
"There is something. Last night, I 
was going through Alexei's wardrobe,  

944
01:43:05,040 --> 01:43:12,720
seeing what I could give away to charity. In 
a jacket pocket, I found a piece of paper,  

945
01:43:12,720 --> 01:43:20,240
rolled up into a ball. It was a short 
message in Russian with no date or address.  

946
01:43:21,360 --> 01:43:30,240
It was a warning and just said: 'I am telling 
you this in the strictest confidence. Mossolov  

947
01:43:30,960 --> 01:43:39,040
could be dangerous. You don't know what you're 
getting involved with.' It was signed 'Victor'."

948
01:43:40,480 --> 01:43:42,560
"You still have the note?" I asked.

949
01:43:43,760 --> 01:43:47,360
Mrs. Romanov opened a desk 
drawer and took out the note.

950
01:43:48,880 --> 01:43:51,840
"Does the name 'Victor' mean 
anything to you?" I asked.

951
01:43:52,960 --> 01:43:54,320
"No," she answered.

952
01:43:55,440 --> 01:44:02,480
"Well, it could be Victor Kamenev who runs a 
business by the name of Kamenev Finance," I said.  

953
01:44:03,680 --> 01:44:09,040
"We'll have to check this out and get back to 
you. Have you informed the police about this?"

954
01:44:10,160 --> 01:44:14,240
"No. There's just been so 
much on my mind..." she began.

955
01:44:15,600 --> 01:44:21,040
"I'd advise you to let them have the note 
immediately, but with your permission,  

956
01:44:21,040 --> 01:44:27,120
I'd rather you didn't tell the NYPD about 
Kamenev until I've checked him out first."

957
01:44:28,800 --> 01:44:34,400
We left the house and made our way to the 
Brighton Beach subway and took an express  

958
01:44:34,400 --> 01:44:42,160
Q train back to Manhattan. At last some pieces 
of the puzzle seemed to be falling into place,  

959
01:44:43,200 --> 01:44:49,600
but we were still a long way from the 
solution. We had another Russian connection.  

960
01:44:50,960 --> 01:44:58,960
I wanted to pay a surprise visit to Mr. Kamenev, 
but I needed support. We could be moving in deep,  

961
01:44:58,960 --> 01:45:07,280
dangerous waters. I made a call on my cell phone 
to Joe Blaney, an ex-NYPD colleague of mine.  

962
01:45:08,480 --> 01:45:15,840
Joe's also an ex-NYPD heavyweight boxing 
champion. He retired a few years ago but  

963
01:45:15,840 --> 01:45:21,360
still looks impressively tough, tough 
enough to scare people into cooperating.  

964
01:45:22,480 --> 01:45:28,000
That's one good reason why he accompanies me 
on any job where there's an element of risk.

965
01:45:29,680 --> 01:45:34,320
"Joe, I have some work for 
you. Are you busy?" I asked.

966
01:45:35,360 --> 01:45:37,360
"I got nothing on," said Joe.

967
01:45:38,880 --> 01:45:43,840
"Meet me at McSorley's Ale House on East 
7th Street at three o'clock, this afternoon.  

968
01:45:45,040 --> 01:45:46,960
I'll give you all the details then."

969
01:45:48,720 --> 01:45:54,720
Stella and I transferred to an uptown train 
at Broadway and Lafayette, and got off at  

970
01:45:54,720 --> 01:46:01,440
Astor Place in the middle of the East Village. 
Joe joined us in the bar just before three.  

971
01:46:02,720 --> 01:46:08,160
I gave him a brief outline of the story so 
far before we left for Kamenev's office.  

972
01:46:09,600 --> 01:46:14,480
On the stairs up to the office, old 
wallpaper was peeling off the walls.  

973
01:46:15,520 --> 01:46:22,800
On the upstairs landing, flattened cigarette butts 
covered the floor. "Elegant, huh?" muttered Joe.

974
01:46:24,400 --> 01:46:32,320
As we entered Kamenev's office, the contrast 
couldn't have been greater. Inside, all was clean,  

975
01:46:32,320 --> 01:46:40,080
neat, and tastefully decorated. The floors were 
polished wood. Everywhere was the latest in  

976
01:46:40,080 --> 01:46:48,080
office technology. In response to our request to 
speak to Kamenev, the receptionist said a little  

977
01:46:48,080 --> 01:46:56,000
too automatically: "You don't have an appointment. 
Sorry, but Mr. Kamenev is busy with a client."

978
01:46:57,440 --> 01:47:00,640
There was no sound of conversation 
coming from his office.

979
01:47:02,160 --> 01:47:06,640
"Seems awfully quiet in there. 
Would you tell him Nat Marley  

980
01:47:06,640 --> 01:47:10,240
wants to speak to him concerning Alexei Romanov."

981
01:47:11,760 --> 01:47:17,520
She gave me a sour look and picked up 
the phone. She spoke briefly to him  

982
01:47:17,520 --> 01:47:25,120
and then turned to me and said, "Seems that Mr. 
Kamenev's not so busy after all. You can go in."

983
01:47:26,880 --> 01:47:35,120
The guy behind the desk had to be Kamenev, a big 
man with rosy cheeks, bushy moustache, and a full  

984
01:47:35,120 --> 01:47:43,120
head of curly hair. You could see his reflection 
in the polished wood of the large desk. Around  

985
01:47:43,120 --> 01:47:49,840
the room were various framed photographs of life 
in the old Russia from the nineteenth century.

986
01:47:50,560 --> 01:47:55,680
"Mr. Kamenev? The name's Nat Marley, 
licensed private investigator.  

987
01:47:56,720 --> 01:48:03,680
This is my assistant Stella Delgado and my 
colleague Joe Blaney. I'll come straight to  

988
01:48:03,680 --> 01:48:08,800
the point. I'm investigating the 
recent murder of Alexei Romanov.  

989
01:48:09,840 --> 01:48:14,880
I believe you may have information concerning 
who was responsible for the killing."

990
01:48:16,240 --> 01:48:21,280
"I don't know anything. Who sent you 
here?" demanded Kamenev nervously.

991
01:48:22,640 --> 01:48:30,320
Kamenev suddenly opened a desk drawer and produced 
an automatic pistol. He pointed it at me with a  

992
01:48:30,320 --> 01:48:38,960
trembling hand. Joe was equally quick. His old 
police special was pointing straight at Kamenev,  

993
01:48:39,520 --> 01:48:41,600
but his hand was rock steady.

994
01:48:42,960 --> 01:48:50,800
"Mr. Kamenev," said Joe smoothly, "it's obvious 
you're no gunman. Let's use some common sense.  

995
01:48:51,680 --> 01:48:54,240
I suggest you put that gun down."

996
01:48:55,680 --> 01:49:01,680
Kamenev sighed and placed the gun 
on the desk. Joe moved to the desk,  

997
01:49:01,680 --> 01:49:06,240
and emptied the bullets out of the 
weapon, then returned it to Kamenev.

998
01:49:07,840 --> 01:49:12,400
"Is it true that you sent a warning 
note to Mr. Romanov?" I asked.

999
01:49:13,760 --> 01:49:17,040
Kamenev eyed us suspiciously from behind his desk.  

1000
01:49:18,320 --> 01:49:23,840
"Before I say anything, I need to have a 
guarantee that you are genuine," he said.

1001
01:49:25,120 --> 01:49:33,120
"By all means. I suggest you call Alexei Romanov's 
widow," I replied and gave him the number.

1002
01:49:34,720 --> 01:49:41,600
A conversation in rapid Russian followed. 
After a while, he put the phone down and  

1003
01:49:41,600 --> 01:49:47,760
looked at us. "My apologies. You 
understand I have to be cautious."

1004
01:49:49,200 --> 01:49:55,840
I glanced around the room again. There were also 
photographs of the old Russian royal family.  

1005
01:49:56,800 --> 01:50:01,040
Nicholas, the last of the 
Czars with Czarina Alexandra.

1006
01:50:02,400 --> 01:50:06,480
"You obviously love your 
country. You must be a patriot.  

1007
01:50:07,440 --> 01:50:14,400
Also, you must have been a friend of Alexei 
Romanov. Who were you trying to protect him from?"

1008
01:50:15,920 --> 01:50:24,080
Silence. After a long pause Kamenev 
spoke: "This is very difficult for me,  

1009
01:50:24,080 --> 01:50:32,640
Mr. Marley. It's really not wise to say anything 
more. If I were you I'd stay away from all this."

1010
01:50:34,080 --> 01:50:41,120
Kamenev looked uncomfortable. I wondered if he 
was too scared to talk, like the bartenders at  

1011
01:50:41,120 --> 01:50:49,760
the Odessa Steps? I tried a different approach. 
Kamenev's business could be benefiting from  

1012
01:50:49,760 --> 01:50:57,520
the money coming in from the illegal immigrant 
operation. I had no proof, but it was worth a try.

1013
01:50:58,880 --> 01:51:06,480
"I want to speak to you about some poor Russian 
boys found dead on Jones Beach. I've heard a rumor  

1014
01:51:06,480 --> 01:51:12,880
that someone was laundering the money these boys 
paid to get into the country, money that needed  

1015
01:51:12,880 --> 01:51:20,000
to be integrated into the legal economy. I 
understand that's your line of business."

1016
01:51:20,000 --> 01:51:21,440
Kamenev remained silent.

1017
01:51:22,720 --> 01:51:29,920
"Is money laundering part of your business?" 
I insisted. Again Kamenev didn't say anything.

1018
01:51:31,360 --> 01:51:38,320
"Let's get one thing straight," I said. "I'm sure 
there's a whole lot of questions the IRS would  

1019
01:51:38,320 --> 01:51:45,440
love to ask about your accounts, but I'm not 
investigating your business. Let's get back to  

1020
01:51:45,440 --> 01:51:53,120
those poor young men who were washed up on Jones 
Beach. Whoever launders the money those boys paid  

1021
01:51:53,120 --> 01:51:59,040
to get into the country might as well have held 
a gun to their heads and pulled the trigger.  

1022
01:52:00,320 --> 01:52:06,640
Would it be you by any chance? You see, 
they died because they'd been put in a  

1023
01:52:06,640 --> 01:52:15,520
boat that was falling apart. The boat split in 
two in the storm and they drowned. In some way  

1024
01:52:15,520 --> 01:52:21,120
you might share some responsibility for 
the deaths of four good Russian boys."

1025
01:52:22,640 --> 01:52:28,320
I could see Kamenev's lips tightening. 
I knew what I said had found its target.  

1026
01:52:29,360 --> 01:52:35,760
I was appealing to his sense of honor. I hoped 
and prayed there was some honor left in him.

1027
01:52:37,280 --> 01:52:44,960
"Four good Russian boys," I repeated. "All they 
wanted was to enter the land of opportunity  

1028
01:52:44,960 --> 01:52:52,960
and make a success of their lives. And now 
they're dead. Their families back in Russia  

1029
01:52:52,960 --> 01:52:59,040
won't know what's happened to them. Maybe they 
saved up for years to give their sons this  

1030
01:52:59,040 --> 01:53:05,280
chance. But you won't be out of pocket. 
The money will still be coming in."

1031
01:53:06,560 --> 01:53:14,400
"Honest to God," stammered Kamenev, "I don't ask 
questions! Their deaths couldn't be my fault."

1032
01:53:15,840 --> 01:53:19,120
"So you were just the honest money launderer,  

1033
01:53:19,120 --> 01:53:25,840
huh?" I asked. "No questions asked 
and nothing on your conscience?"

1034
01:53:25,840 --> 01:53:30,640
Kamenev remained silent. Sweat 
started to form on his forehead.

1035
01:53:31,920 --> 01:53:36,160
"I have this feeling there's a 
connection between Romanov's death  

1036
01:53:36,160 --> 01:53:42,880
and those boys found drowned on Jones Beach. 
You follow what I'm saying?" I went on.

1037
01:53:44,000 --> 01:53:46,720
He nodded, but his expression was blank.

1038
01:53:48,160 --> 01:53:55,360
"I think you can help," I continued. "Help us 
find the guys who sent those good Russians to  

1039
01:53:55,360 --> 01:54:03,200
their deaths. You're a patriot, and despite your 
line of business, I believe you're a man of honor.  

1040
01:54:04,240 --> 01:54:10,240
The most patriotic thing you could do 
is help us to find whoever is exploiting  

1041
01:54:10,240 --> 01:54:16,880
honest Russian people. We also want to 
find who really killed Alexei Romanov.  

1042
01:54:18,000 --> 01:54:23,360
That man did some fine work in the community, 
helping Russian folks to settle here."

1043
01:54:24,720 --> 01:54:30,480
He remained silent. I nodded to 
Stella. "Tell him," I said to her.

1044
01:54:31,760 --> 01:54:39,120
"Mr. Kamenev," Stella began, "our interest 
in this case is also personal. My brother,  

1045
01:54:39,120 --> 01:54:44,320
Jose De La Cruz has been wrongly 
accused of Alexei Romanov's murder.  

1046
01:54:45,360 --> 01:54:52,960
As far as the NYPD are concerned he's guilty. 
We believe he was set up as the fall guy,  

1047
01:54:52,960 --> 01:54:58,320
to take the blame. We need someone 
who knows the Russian community,  

1048
01:54:58,960 --> 01:55:05,840
someone who has the contacts and inside knowledge, 
to help bring the real killers to justice.

1049
01:55:07,440 --> 01:55:16,160
Kamenev took a deep breath and pushed his hands 
into his fists. "OK," said Kamenev, "I admit that  

1050
01:55:16,160 --> 01:55:24,960
in my work, I don't ask too many questions. 
Cash arrives from anonymous clients. I only know  

1051
01:55:24,960 --> 01:55:32,400
them by a number. But if innocent Russian boys 
have been killed and I've profited from it..."

1052
01:55:33,360 --> 01:55:39,360
I interrupted him. "You still haven't told 
me why you sent the warning note to Romanov.  

1053
01:55:40,320 --> 01:55:41,360
Who's Mossolov?"

1054
01:55:42,480 --> 01:55:46,160
"Mossolov runs some sort of 
operation in Brighton Beach  

1055
01:55:46,960 --> 01:55:54,160
and contacts me from time to time to 
expect a delivery of cash. We've never met,  

1056
01:55:54,720 --> 01:56:04,640
only exchanged coded emails and faxes. Monday last 
week, Mossolov emailed me and asked what I knew  

1057
01:56:04,640 --> 01:56:15,280
about Romanov. I asked why and the reply was that 
Romanov had been asking inconvenient questions. I  

1058
01:56:15,280 --> 01:56:22,240
didn't want to get involved, so I just played it 
safe and denied any knowledge of Romanov, except  

1059
01:56:22,240 --> 01:56:31,360
what's known publicly. I suspected that Mossolov 
was dangerous and so Romanov could be in danger."

1060
01:56:32,800 --> 01:56:42,240
"Thank you, Mr. Kamenev. Our problem is that we 
still have to prove who murdered Romanov," I said.

1061
01:56:42,240 --> 01:56:49,520
"Mr. Marley, I am a patriot, and I feel I 
owe a debt of honor towards my countrymen.  

1062
01:56:50,640 --> 01:56:51,680
How can I help?"

1063
01:56:53,040 --> 01:56:57,200
"I'm going to set up a meeting with 
Alexei Romanov's widow," I said.  

1064
01:56:58,160 --> 01:57:03,920
"I'd like you to be there. Expect 
a call from me tomorrow morning.
 
 

1065
01:57:07,680 --> 01:57:08,400
CHAPTER TEN

1066
01:57:09,520 --> 01:57:09,840
Witness

1067
01:57:12,320 --> 01:57:19,520
It was now just over a week since Alexei 
Romanov had been found murdered. People's  

1068
01:57:19,520 --> 01:57:23,840
memories tend to fade once events 
become part of the distant past.  

1069
01:57:25,200 --> 01:57:32,480
We needed to find witnesses while their memories 
were still fresh. Maybe the presence of Kamenev  

1070
01:57:32,480 --> 01:57:37,840
would help the bartenders at the Odessa 
Steps to remember more about Wednesday night.

1071
01:57:39,520 --> 01:57:47,280
I left Stella to do some phoning to set up a 
meeting with Kamenev and Mrs. Romanov. I suggested  

1072
01:57:47,280 --> 01:57:53,040
somewhere like a good restaurant in the Brighton 
Beach area, but I left the choice up to her.  

1073
01:57:54,560 --> 01:58:01,200
I had received another Coast Guard press 
release. Another body washed up on Jones Beach.  

1074
01:58:02,400 --> 01:58:05,840
The details were similar to 
those of the other victims:  

1075
01:58:06,560 --> 01:58:11,360
a male, in his twenties. No form 
of identification on the body.  

1076
01:58:12,480 --> 01:58:17,200
No definite connection could be made with 
the previous fatalities on Jones Beach.

1077
01:58:18,720 --> 01:58:25,120
But if there was a connection, just how many 
people had been on board that lifeboat when it  

1078
01:58:25,120 --> 01:58:32,080
left the ship for the Long Island shore? With the 
information about deaths of innocent Russian boys,  

1079
01:58:32,640 --> 01:58:39,040
I didn't anticipate too much difficulty in gaining 
the cooperation of the citizens of Brighton Beach.

1080
01:58:40,640 --> 01:58:44,560
I had just finished reading the 
press release when the phone rang.  

1081
01:58:45,440 --> 01:58:49,760
I recognized the elegant 
English accent - Edie Tilden.

1082
01:58:51,120 --> 01:58:56,800
"Mr. Marley, I've seen a very 
suspicious incident, on Fire Island."

1083
01:58:57,840 --> 01:59:02,640
Had I been wise to encourage that eccentric 
old lady to play the investigator?

1084
01:59:03,920 --> 01:59:06,000
"Tell me all about it," I said.

1085
01:59:07,120 --> 01:59:12,480
"I spent yesterday beachcombing 
along the eastern tip of Fire Island.  

1086
01:59:13,120 --> 01:59:19,600
And I saw this man who didn't look like 
he really belonged on a beach," she said.

1087
01:59:20,720 --> 01:59:23,120
"What do you mean by 'didn't belong'?"

1088
01:59:24,320 --> 01:59:32,000
"He wasn't dressed properly. Too formal. 
He was wearing an overcoat over a gray  

1089
01:59:32,000 --> 01:59:39,200
suit. Shiny black shoes. He was looking 
out at the ocean through binoculars,  

1090
01:59:39,760 --> 01:59:43,840
but I don't think he was watching the wildlife."

1091
01:59:44,400 --> 01:59:46,480
"Could you describe him?" I asked.

1092
01:59:47,520 --> 01:59:54,640
"Well, he was tall, six feet 
plus, with a big build. But,  

1093
01:59:54,640 --> 02:00:02,960
you see, Mr. Marley, I saw all this from a 
distance. As soon as I got closer, he left."

1094
02:00:04,320 --> 02:00:07,200
Perhaps he was frightened 
by the sight of Edie Tilden.  

1095
02:00:08,240 --> 02:00:15,360
What she had witnessed could be relevant or 
could have been entirely innocent. Fire Island  

1096
02:00:15,360 --> 02:00:21,440
is the next narrow strip of land off the Long 
Island mainland, to the east of Jones Beach.  

1097
02:00:22,800 --> 02:00:29,280
Anyway, I stored away the information, thanked 
her, and returned to our immediate concerns.

1098
02:00:30,960 --> 02:00:37,680
Stella had made the necessary arrangements: a 
midday meeting at Cafe Paris in Brighton Beach.  

1099
02:00:38,960 --> 02:00:45,120
A table had been booked, and Kamenev was 
on his way to pick us up. It would be a  

1100
02:00:45,120 --> 02:00:50,080
pleasant change to travel to Brighton 
Beach by car instead of the subway.

1101
02:00:51,760 --> 02:00:57,520
Things with Kamenev were now more relaxed, so 
we were able to get to know one another a little  

1102
02:00:57,520 --> 02:01:05,440
better. Victor Kamenev's family, we learned, left 
Russia and settled in America many years ago.  

1103
02:01:06,720 --> 02:01:11,600
Like many in the Russian-American 
community, Russian was his first language,  

1104
02:01:12,240 --> 02:01:16,800
and he and his relatives had remained 
true to their cultural roots.

1105
02:01:18,320 --> 02:01:22,320
The car was now leaving Manhattan, 
crossing the Brooklyn Bridge.  

1106
02:01:23,520 --> 02:01:31,360
Below, the wind was whipping up the waters of 
the East River into white-tipped waves. Above us,  

1107
02:01:31,920 --> 02:01:40,080
on the footbridge, people were walking into 
Manhattan, well wrapped-up against the cold. Soon  

1108
02:01:40,080 --> 02:01:46,560
we were cruising along Flatbush Avenue, with the 
skyscrapers of Manhattan fading into the distance.

1109
02:01:48,080 --> 02:01:56,400
The conversation turned to recent events. "Mr. 
Marley," Kamenev started, "I've been thinking  

1110
02:01:56,400 --> 02:02:02,640
a lot about our conversation yesterday. 
I'll ask whatever questions you want me to.  

1111
02:02:03,760 --> 02:02:10,800
I can put pressure on people and ask for favors. 
There are people around Brighton Beach who owe  

1112
02:02:10,800 --> 02:02:17,840
me money. The prospect of negotiating a 
debt should encourage someone to talk."

1113
02:02:18,800 --> 02:02:25,360
The car was now rolling through the suburbs of 
Brooklyn. The rest of the journey passed sociably.  

1114
02:02:26,720 --> 02:02:31,760
On arriving at the Cafe Paris, we 
met Mrs. Romanov, who was waiting in  

1115
02:02:31,760 --> 02:02:37,760
the reception area. We were taken over to 
our table where I made the introductions.

1116
02:02:39,360 --> 02:02:45,840
"Mrs. Romanov. You've already met 
Stella and this is Mr. Victor Kamenev.  

1117
02:02:46,720 --> 02:02:49,840
Mr. Kamenev is as anxious as you are to get  

1118
02:02:49,840 --> 02:02:55,520
justice for your husband. Mr. Kamenev sent 
the warning note to your late husband."

1119
02:02:57,120 --> 02:03:05,440
Not surprisingly, Mrs. Romanov looked extremely 
tense. After ordering, Mrs. Romanov questioned  

1120
02:03:05,440 --> 02:03:14,080
Kamenev. A long conversation in Russian. To 
begin with, Mrs. Romanov's voice was sharp.  

1121
02:03:15,120 --> 02:03:20,960
I held my breath and crossed my fingers, 
but soon she sounded much friendlier.  

1122
02:03:21,920 --> 02:03:29,920
I breathed out. Then, they shook hands 
warmly. Mrs. Romanov addressed everybody.  

1123
02:03:31,200 --> 02:03:40,320
"I'm sorry about that. I needed to be absolutely 
sure about Mr. Kamenev. Now, I feel I can trust  

1124
02:03:40,320 --> 02:03:48,960
him. This is a very difficult time for me. It's 
little more than a week since poor Alexei was so  

1125
02:03:48,960 --> 02:03:57,440
cruelly murdered. I want to thank you all 
very sincerely for coming here. Mr. Marley,  

1126
02:03:57,440 --> 02:04:06,240
I know you said your interest in this case was 
personal. Naturally, mine is too. I know you must  

1127
02:04:06,240 --> 02:04:12,560
have other work you should be doing, and this 
investigation must be a considerable expense."

1128
02:04:13,920 --> 02:04:16,560
"Well, not really, ma'am..." I began.

1129
02:04:17,920 --> 02:04:21,040
"Mr. Marley, you're a very poor liar.  

1130
02:04:22,000 --> 02:04:27,520
I'm hiring you to find my husband's 
murderer. Whatever the cost."

1131
02:04:29,120 --> 02:04:35,920
I could certainly use the money. I hadn't done any 
other work since I'd heard the news about Jose.  

1132
02:04:36,960 --> 02:04:40,960
And there was still the office 
rent, taxes, and salaries to pay.

1133
02:04:42,400 --> 02:04:46,800
"Thank you, ma'am, I accept. 
Stella will draw up a contract."

1134
02:04:48,720 --> 02:04:54,800
After a discussion over lunch, there seemed 
to be two clear avenues of investigation.  

1135
02:04:56,080 --> 02:05:02,800
One was the Odessa Steps. Having a member of 
the Russian community with us could help to  

1136
02:05:02,800 --> 02:05:10,720
make some progress there. The other avenue was 
Alexei Romanov's computer files, particularly  

1137
02:05:10,720 --> 02:05:18,800
those concerning the Immigrant Welfare Society. 
Computer skills were Stella's specialty, so she  

1138
02:05:18,800 --> 02:05:25,120
left with Mrs. Romanov to examine the computer, 
while I paid a visit to the bar with Kamenev.

1139
02:05:26,720 --> 02:05:33,120
When we arrived, the lunchtime crowd was 
building up. I took Victor over to the  

1140
02:05:33,120 --> 02:05:39,040
display of sports souvenirs. I showed 
him the baseball bat Jose had grabbed.  

1141
02:05:40,160 --> 02:05:47,600
The bat was now securely fixed to the wall 
with metal bands and strong screws. I gave  

1142
02:05:47,600 --> 02:05:53,680
Kamenev all the background information he might 
need about Jose's night out in Brighton Beach.

1143
02:05:55,200 --> 02:06:02,000
I recognized the bartender I'd spoken with on 
my previous visit. He was laughing and joking  

1144
02:06:02,000 --> 02:06:08,880
with the regular customers. His face dropped 
as soon as he saw me holding up Jose's picture.

1145
02:06:10,240 --> 02:06:16,320
"Remember me?" I asked. "I was asking you 
about this guy who'd been drinking here  

1146
02:06:16,320 --> 02:06:19,680
last Wednesday night. His name's Jose  

1147
02:06:20,320 --> 02:06:26,000
and he's in a lot of trouble. I got the 
impression you were suffering from a little  

1148
02:06:26,000 --> 02:06:33,680
memory loss. Or maybe you were just confused. 
I've brought a friend along to help you remember."

1149
02:06:35,200 --> 02:06:40,560
The bartender stood there silently. 
Sweat started to form on his forehead.  

1150
02:06:41,520 --> 02:06:45,520
He looked like a frightened 
animal, nervous and vulnerable.

1151
02:06:46,720 --> 02:06:52,080
"I didn't see nothing. I swear I 
didn't see nothing," he repeated.

1152
02:06:53,360 --> 02:06:59,920
Meanwhile, a smartly dressed guy, who I took 
to be the manager, joined the bartender.

1153
02:07:01,040 --> 02:07:06,800
"What's going on here?" he asked. 
"I'll have no harassment of my staff."

1154
02:07:08,400 --> 02:07:14,480
The moment he made eye contact with Kamenev, 
the manager froze and lowered his head.  

1155
02:07:16,240 --> 02:07:24,000
Victor spoke to him in Russian. It sounded like a 
heated argument at first, but tempers soon cooled.  

1156
02:07:25,280 --> 02:07:30,560
The manager waved to the bartender who 
poured drinks for Kamenev and myself.

1157
02:07:32,160 --> 02:07:37,440
"Mikhail, the bar manager, has just 
remembered how much in debt he is to me.  

1158
02:07:38,480 --> 02:07:43,840
I've offered to be flexible about the 
repayments, provided we get some information.  

1159
02:07:44,960 --> 02:07:47,200
Shall we move into your office, Mikhail?"

1160
02:07:48,720 --> 02:07:57,520
The bartender told us that Jose had woken up in 
the bar alone. He was sleepy and confused. He  

1161
02:07:57,520 --> 02:08:06,240
stood up, reached out an arm, grabbed the baseball 
bat, fell over and just lay there. The regular  

1162
02:08:06,240 --> 02:08:12,640
customers at the bar were very offended. 
Who was this guy damaging the sacred bat?  

1163
02:08:14,080 --> 02:08:20,720
Before anyone could lay a hand on him, someone 
else had got involved and protected Jose from  

1164
02:08:20,720 --> 02:08:27,760
the furious regulars. This guy had taken 
pity on him and said he'd help get him home.

1165
02:08:29,360 --> 02:08:33,440
I was getting very interested indeed. There were  

1166
02:08:33,440 --> 02:08:38,080
a whole lot of questions I needed 
to ask via Kamenev's interpreting.

1167
02:08:39,520 --> 02:08:43,440
"The guy who helped Jose. Name?" I asked.

1168
02:08:44,560 --> 02:08:49,840
The bartender paused and looked fearfully 
toward his boss, who nodded his permission.

1169
02:08:51,120 --> 02:08:55,840
"He's called Nick Zernov. If 
you know what's good for you,  

1170
02:08:55,840 --> 02:08:59,680
you'll stay clear of him. He's a real bad guy."

1171
02:09:01,280 --> 02:09:06,400
That explained why he had the power 
to protect Jose from an angry crowd.  

1172
02:09:07,680 --> 02:09:15,840
Zernov had seen the opportunity to use Jose as the 
fall guy to make Jose appear guilty for a murder.

1173
02:09:17,360 --> 02:09:20,960
"Give me a full description 
of Zernov, will you," I asked.

1174
02:09:22,080 --> 02:09:30,800
"Tall, over six feet, and muscular. 
Black hair cut really short. Thick black  

1175
02:09:30,800 --> 02:09:39,360
eyebrows. His nose looks like someone broke it. 
Likes to wear expensive suits, shiny material."

1176
02:09:40,960 --> 02:09:44,640
I experienced that thrill you get when you realize  

1177
02:09:44,640 --> 02:09:48,720
some parts of the puzzle might 
at last be fitting together.  

1178
02:09:50,000 --> 02:09:57,600
I recalled Edie Tilden's description of the guy 
she'd seen on Fire Island. I had to remind myself  

1179
02:09:57,600 --> 02:10:05,440
not to get over-excited. We still had nothing 
concrete yet. I continued with the questioning.

1180
02:10:06,720 --> 02:10:09,920
"How drunk was Jose? Could he stand up?"

1181
02:10:11,040 --> 02:10:16,880
"He was a bit unsteady after Zernov 
picked him up, but otherwise OK.  

1182
02:10:18,160 --> 02:10:25,680
He had a few more drinks and then Zernov took him 
outside. That's all I know," the bartender said.

1183
02:10:26,960 --> 02:10:34,480
"You know this guy Jose is facing a murder 
charge. They think he killed Alexei Romanov.  

1184
02:10:35,680 --> 02:10:41,840
Jose was just a harmless drunk. I don't 
believe he is the killer," I said.

1185
02:10:43,200 --> 02:10:46,480
The name Romanov meant something to the bartender.  

1186
02:10:47,360 --> 02:10:55,840
His face brightened. "Mr. Romanov helped 
me and my family. Such a good man."

1187
02:10:56,640 --> 02:11:03,120
I had a final question. "Would you be prepared 
to tell the police what you've just told us?"

1188
02:11:04,400 --> 02:11:10,880
Another discussion in Russian between Kamenev 
and the bartender. The bartender frowned  

1189
02:11:10,880 --> 02:11:16,400
and shook his head. Then he said 
something, almost in a whisper.  

1190
02:11:17,680 --> 02:11:26,240
Before I got the translation, I knew it meant 
'No'. The bartender was clearly terrified.
 
 

1191
02:11:29,920 --> 02:11:30,880
CHAPTER ELEVEN

1192
02:11:32,000 --> 02:11:32,640
Progress

1193
02:11:34,720 --> 02:11:41,680
It was time to see how Stella had been doing at 
the Romanov house with the computer files. As  

1194
02:11:41,680 --> 02:11:49,760
Kamenev's car rolled along Shore Boulevard, I was 
thinking about the case. I told Kamenev my theory.

1195
02:11:51,040 --> 02:11:56,080
"Victor, I think we have enough new 
information to encourage the police  

1196
02:11:56,080 --> 02:12:03,520
to follow a new line of investigation. We now 
know that Jose left the bar with a guy who has  

1197
02:12:03,520 --> 02:12:09,680
local criminal connections. Zernov doesn't 
sound like the type of guy who'd rescue  

1198
02:12:09,680 --> 02:12:14,960
someone from a beating purely out of warm, 
sympathetic feelings toward his fellow men.  

1199
02:12:16,240 --> 02:12:22,400
So my theory is that Zernov saw an 
opportunity to use Jose as the fall guy."

1200
02:12:23,920 --> 02:12:26,960
"But what about all the 
evidence against your client?  

1201
02:12:27,680 --> 02:12:31,920
The forensics? And the murder 
weapon?" asked Kamenev.

1202
02:12:33,360 --> 02:12:36,720
"It'd be quite easy for Zernov to kill Romanov,"  

1203
02:12:36,720 --> 02:12:43,360
I explained. "Then, for him to wipe the 
gun clean, grip Jose's hand around it,  

1204
02:12:43,920 --> 02:12:50,560
leaving his fingerprints on the gun. Even 
easier to do if Jose was already unconscious."

1205
02:12:52,400 --> 02:12:58,640
Back at the house, Stella had found 
something. A file protected by a password.  

1206
02:12:59,840 --> 02:13:05,760
Whatever she tried, family names or 
place names, she couldn't open the file.  

1207
02:13:07,280 --> 02:13:11,760
I glanced around the room. There 
were a number of photographs of  

1208
02:13:11,760 --> 02:13:18,080
old Russia. Opposite the desk was a 
picture of a wide avenue in a major city.

1209
02:13:19,680 --> 02:13:22,560
Mrs. Romanov noticed me studying the picture.  

1210
02:13:23,920 --> 02:13:31,360
"Poor Alexei loved that street scene," 
she said. "It's the Nevsky Prospekt  

1211
02:13:31,360 --> 02:13:40,320
in old St. Petersburg. That's an idea! Why 
don't you try typing in 'Nevsky Prospekt'."

1212
02:13:41,760 --> 02:13:44,640
"Could you spell that out for me?" asked Stella.

1213
02:13:46,080 --> 02:13:48,880
Again, the computer denied us access.  

1214
02:13:50,000 --> 02:13:58,160
Stella keyed in the words individually, but still 
no success. Mrs. Romanov had another suggestion.

1215
02:13:59,360 --> 02:14:07,040
"That street is named after the Russian 
national hero, Alexander Nevsky. Try his name,"  

1216
02:14:07,600 --> 02:14:09,120
suggested Mrs. Romanov.

1217
02:14:10,560 --> 02:14:15,920
Stella keyed in the words. This 
time the protected file opened.  

1218
02:14:17,040 --> 02:14:22,640
There were lists of dates going back over 
the past two years at regular intervals.  

1219
02:14:23,840 --> 02:14:29,200
Next to some of the dates were Russian 
names, sometimes with local addresses.  

1220
02:14:30,640 --> 02:14:37,520
By some of the names there was a capital 'M' 
with a question mark. The most recent date  

1221
02:14:37,520 --> 02:14:45,200
was last Friday. There were also a couple 
of future dates with an 'M?' next to them.  

1222
02:14:46,480 --> 02:14:50,160
The first of these was Saturday March 16th.

1223
02:14:51,920 --> 02:14:54,480
"What do you make of that?" asked Stella.

1224
02:14:55,680 --> 02:15:00,480
"Well, 'M' could stand for 
Mossolov," said Kamenev.

1225
02:15:02,000 --> 02:15:09,840
"OK. If we assume that Zernov works for 
Mossolov," I said, "and if we can find out  

1226
02:15:09,840 --> 02:15:16,240
what sort of operation Mossolov is running, 
then things should fall into place."

1227
02:15:18,080 --> 02:15:25,120
Mrs. Romanov had been examining the names 
and dates in the computer file. "Mr. Marley,  

1228
02:15:25,760 --> 02:15:32,240
I know some of these names. Some of them are 
people who Alexei helped through the Immigrant  

1229
02:15:32,240 --> 02:15:43,040
Welfare Society. This one here, Boris Tchernov, 
I know he entered the country illegally. Could  

1230
02:15:43,040 --> 02:15:50,400
Mossolov be smuggling in Russian immigrants? Could 
these be the dates when they were brought in?"

1231
02:15:52,080 --> 02:15:59,680
"It's possible, but we'd still need more proof," 
I answered. "I'd like to talk to Tchernov, but it  

1232
02:15:59,680 --> 02:16:06,080
would be helpful if you would accompany me, Mrs. 
Romanov, so there's someone he knows and trusts.  

1233
02:16:07,360 --> 02:16:13,760
But that will have to wait until tomorrow. It's 
time I had another talk with Captain Oldenberg.  

1234
02:16:14,880 --> 02:16:18,800
Stella, would you print me out a 
couple of hard copies of that file?"

1235
02:16:20,560 --> 02:16:25,520
We said our goodbyes to Mrs. Romanov 
and left with Kamenev in his car.  

1236
02:16:26,960 --> 02:16:31,920
Kamenev dropped us off at 
Police Plaza in Manhattan.

1237
02:16:31,920 --> 02:16:34,480
A sergeant led us to Oldenberg's office.  

1238
02:16:35,600 --> 02:16:41,680
Oldenberg was sitting with his feet up on the desk 
and didn't bother to remove them when we entered.

1239
02:16:43,040 --> 02:16:47,439
"Please don't stand up just 
for us, Oldenberg," I said.

1240
02:16:48,880 --> 02:16:55,520
"What made you think I would?" growled the 
captain. "I don't suppose you want some coffee."

1241
02:16:56,720 --> 02:17:02,400
"Thanks for the hospitality, but if 
it's NYPD coffee we'll do without it."

1242
02:17:03,600 --> 02:17:08,400
"Sensible decision. Now what 
can I do for you, Marley?"  

1243
02:17:08,399 --> 02:17:12,000
he asked, at last removing his feet from the desk.

1244
02:17:13,680 --> 02:17:20,160
There was the usual expression on the captain's 
face which seemed to say that life and work were  

1245
02:17:20,160 --> 02:17:27,840
an annoyance, and I wasn't making things any 
better. It was time to get him interested.

1246
02:17:28,399 --> 02:17:31,839
"The Odessa Steps, Brighton Beach," I began.  

1247
02:17:32,720 --> 02:17:38,960
"You remember I told you that Jose pulled 
that baseball bat off the wall and then got  

1248
02:17:38,960 --> 02:17:45,439
out of that bar unharmed? Well, the 
reason was that he had a protector."

1249
02:17:46,880 --> 02:17:51,440
"Go on, Marley. You're beginning 
to interest me," said Oldenberg.

1250
02:17:52,880 --> 02:17:58,000
"I also got a witness, but I doubt whether 
he'd give a statement to the police.  

1251
02:17:59,120 --> 02:18:04,479
A bartender saw Jose leave the bar 
with a big, smartly dressed guy.  

1252
02:18:05,760 --> 02:18:10,880
We have a name - Nick Zernov. 
He's part of a local gang."

1253
02:18:12,319 --> 02:18:14,639
"How do you spell that?" asked the captain.

1254
02:18:16,080 --> 02:18:22,479
There was a rare burst of energy from Oldenberg 
as he swung around in his chair to the computer  

1255
02:18:23,040 --> 02:18:31,120
and typed in the name. A list of names came 
up on the screen, including a Nicholai Zernov.

1256
02:18:32,720 --> 02:18:37,840
"He's known as Nick, so this Nicholai 
could be the guy," I suggested.

1257
02:18:39,439 --> 02:18:47,439
Oldenberg opened the file. The photo matched 
the bartender's description. Zernov had a long  

1258
02:18:47,439 --> 02:18:56,719
criminal record. Like the bartender in the Odessa 
Steps had said, he was a guy to avoid. He'd been  

1259
02:18:56,720 --> 02:19:03,520
charged with murder but found not guilty and had 
served a four-year prison sentence for robbery.

1260
02:19:04,960 --> 02:19:09,760
"Oldenberg, I'm positive that's 
the guy who killed Romanov,"  

1261
02:19:09,760 --> 02:19:14,080
I said. "Would you print me out a 
couple of copies of the picture?"

1262
02:19:15,680 --> 02:19:18,960
"So if he is, where's your proof?"  

1263
02:19:19,680 --> 02:19:23,760
demanded Oldenberg. "I don't have 
anything to charge him with."

1264
02:19:25,120 --> 02:19:31,599
"Well, let's provide you with more new 
evidence," I continued. "You already know  

1265
02:19:31,600 --> 02:19:39,121
about the warning note which Mrs. Romanov found in 
her husband's jacket. I've found the guy who wrote  

1266
02:19:39,120 --> 02:19:47,840
it - a Victor Kamenev, who owns Kamenev Finance. 
He has a lot of contacts in the Russian community.  

1267
02:19:48,720 --> 02:19:55,281
He discovered that Romanov had been doing some 
personal investigation into what could be an  

1268
02:19:55,280 --> 02:20:02,080
illegal immigrant-smuggling operation. But his 
questions had really bothered someone by the  

1269
02:20:02,080 --> 02:20:09,840
name of Mossolov. Kamenev knew Mossolov was 
angry, so he sent the warning note to Romanov."

1270
02:20:11,200 --> 02:20:16,880
"OK, let's check to see if there's 
anything on this Mossolov," said Oldenberg.  

1271
02:20:18,080 --> 02:20:24,640
He typed in the name, but the screen remained 
blank. He paused and thought for a moment.

1272
02:20:25,840 --> 02:20:32,400
"If I'm going to charge Zernov, I need 
solid evidence. We have nothing on him  

1273
02:20:32,399 --> 02:20:36,240
except for the fact he left the 
Odessa Steps with De La Cruz.  

1274
02:20:37,280 --> 02:20:42,240
It'll be easier to find evidence against 
Zernov if he's under the impression that  

1275
02:20:42,240 --> 02:20:47,439
De La Cruz is charged with murder. You 
see where this is leading, Marley?"

1276
02:20:48,720 --> 02:20:55,040
"You mean the official NYPD line is 
that Jose is the killer, case closed.  

1277
02:20:56,000 --> 02:21:01,920
The unofficial line is that the investigation 
quietly continues," I suggested.

1278
02:21:03,200 --> 02:21:06,880
"You got it," said Oldenberg. "I'll have a police  

1279
02:21:06,880 --> 02:21:11,840
surveillance team watch Zernov's 
movements without being seen."

1280
02:21:12,640 --> 02:21:18,080
Suddenly Stellas cell phone rang. She 
rushed out into the hallway to answer it.  

1281
02:21:19,120 --> 02:21:24,000
There was a scream of joy followed 
by rapid Spanish conversation.  

1282
02:21:25,120 --> 02:21:30,080
She rushed back in to the room with 
tears in her eyes and grinning broadly.

1283
02:21:31,280 --> 02:21:39,840
"Nat! That was Mom. Jose's going to be all 
right. He regained consciousness this afternoon  

1284
02:21:40,720 --> 02:21:46,160
and he's been talking to her. The doctors 
think the operation was a success."

1285
02:21:47,520 --> 02:21:51,760
"That's great news, Stella. 
Now if you'll excuse us,  

1286
02:21:51,760 --> 02:21:54,880
Oldenberg, we need to get over to the hospital."

1287
02:21:56,399 --> 02:22:02,240
"OK, Marley," said Oldenberg. "I'll call 
the guard and tell him to expect you."

1288
02:22:04,319 --> 02:22:07,840
The rush hour traffic was 
crawling through Manhattan.  

1289
02:22:08,960 --> 02:22:16,240
To avoid the chaos on the streets, we took the 
subway uptown from City Hall to 103rd Street.  

1290
02:22:17,439 --> 02:22:21,839
From there it was only a few 
blocks walk to the hospital.  

1291
02:22:22,399 --> 02:22:30,479
Stella ran on ahead. I finally reached Jose's 
room, and through the window saw Stella sitting  

1292
02:22:30,479 --> 02:22:38,719
beside the bed smiling at Jose. I knocked softly 
on the door. Stella came out into the hall.

1293
02:22:40,160 --> 02:22:49,359
"Nat," said Stella, "strict orders from the 
nurse. Don't get Jose over-excited. He can talk  

1294
02:22:49,359 --> 02:22:56,960
but it's all a big effort. He just needs plenty 
of rest. We've only been allowed ten minutes."

1295
02:22:58,399 --> 02:23:00,719
Jose recognized me as I walked in.  

1296
02:23:02,240 --> 02:23:09,920
"Nat, thanks for what you did on the roof. It's 
all a bit vague, but I'm told you saved my life."

1297
02:23:11,359 --> 02:23:15,200
"Don't worry," I replied. "Everything's OK now."

1298
02:23:16,720 --> 02:23:23,520
"What do you mean 'OK'?" he asked, trying to 
sit up in bed. "I'm facing a murder charge!"

1299
02:23:24,720 --> 02:23:32,400
"Come on, Jose. Just lie down and try to 
relax," said Stella. "You've got to rest."  

1300
02:23:33,600 --> 02:23:36,480
She smiled at him and gently stroked his hand.

1301
02:23:37,840 --> 02:23:46,400
As soon as Jose was calmer, I spoke to him again. 
"Jose, we've spent the last week investigating.  

1302
02:23:47,120 --> 02:23:55,359
We're turning up new evidence all the time. Just 
trust us. We're doing everything possible to clear  

1303
02:23:55,359 --> 02:24:01,839
your name. I want you to concentrate 
on recovering. Be a good patient."

1304
02:24:03,120 --> 02:24:11,359
"Nat, I can remember something," said Jose. 
"When I woke up in the bar, Miguel and Carlos  

1305
02:24:11,359 --> 02:24:20,240
weren't around. I stood up but lost my balance. 
I reached out and grabbed the first thing I saw  

1306
02:24:20,240 --> 02:24:29,519
to stop myself from falling. It came off in 
my hand. Then there I was, lying on the floor  

1307
02:24:29,520 --> 02:24:35,920
with all these angry guys looking at me. I 
can't remember what happened after that."

1308
02:24:37,200 --> 02:24:38,800
"Thanks, Jose," I said.

1309
02:24:40,000 --> 02:24:49,280
It was time to leave Jose to rest. I succeeded in 
persuading Stella to go home. Before going back to  

1310
02:24:49,280 --> 02:24:56,160
Queens, I thought I should stop by at East 43rd 
Street to check if there had been any messages.  

1311
02:24:57,520 --> 02:25:03,281
An email had arrived from Commander 
Lockhart of the U.S. Coast Guard. It read:
 
 

1312
02:25:04,319 --> 02:25:05,519
Dear Mr. Marley

1313
02:25:06,319 --> 02:25:13,599
Please contact me as soon as possible. We have 
some new evidence here that may be connected  

1314
02:25:13,600 --> 02:25:20,720
with the wrecked lifeboat and fatalities at 
Jones Beach. It's a Russian fishing boat,  

1315
02:25:20,720 --> 02:25:26,000
which was wrecked on Jones Beach last 
night. I'd like to show it to you.

1316
02:25:27,120 --> 02:25:29,519
Best wishes Jim Lockhart

1317
02:25:30,080 --> 02:25:33,280
Commander, U.S. Coast Guard Group Moriches
 
 

1318
02:25:35,120 --> 02:25:42,399
I was very interested indeed. I called Lockhart 
immediately to confirm that I would be there  

1319
02:25:42,399 --> 02:25:52,240
in the morning. Enough investigating 
for one day. It was time to go home.
 
 

1320
02:25:52,240 --> 02:25:53,120
CHAPTER TWELVE

1321
02:25:54,000 --> 02:25:55,920
Wreck on Jones Beach

1322
02:25:58,080 --> 02:26:04,399
After the recent storms, the weather was now 
calmer, with the prospect of spring in the air.  

1323
02:26:05,680 --> 02:26:12,320
I'd called Stella to tell her I was on my way 
to Jones Beach to inspect the fishing boat that  

1324
02:26:12,319 --> 02:26:19,920
Lockhart had told me about. Stella's instructions 
were for her to set up a meeting with Mrs. Romanov  

1325
02:26:19,920 --> 02:26:27,520
that afternoon. Lockhart had arranged to meet me 
at Babylon Station on the Long Island Rail Road,  

1326
02:26:28,399 --> 02:26:34,399
then to take me across the bay to the eastern 
end of Jones Beach to the site of the wreck.

1327
02:26:35,920 --> 02:26:43,600
It was an ancient-looking rusty boat. The force 
of the storm had driven it sideways onto the beach  

1328
02:26:43,600 --> 02:26:51,040
above the normal high-tide mark. It lay there on 
the sand and stones, leaning at a slight angle.  

1329
02:26:52,319 --> 02:26:58,960
Barriers had been set up around the boat. A Coast 
Guard officer stood by a ladder leading up to  

1330
02:26:58,960 --> 02:27:07,680
the deck. On board, Lockhart gave me the full 
story of what had happened. The previous day,  

1331
02:27:07,680 --> 02:27:14,000
in the early evening, the boat had been reported 
to the Coast Guard by a local fishing boat as  

1332
02:27:14,000 --> 02:27:21,760
a potential danger to shipping. Its engine had 
failed and it was drifting helplessly off Jones  

1333
02:27:21,760 --> 02:27:30,560
Beach. No emergency signals had been received. The 
crew of the local boat had tried to assist, but  

1334
02:27:30,560 --> 02:27:38,640
the offer of help was rejected. "Have a good look 
around," said Lockhart. "Tell me what you think."

1335
02:27:40,240 --> 02:27:45,439
I'm no sailor, but I wouldn't have felt 
confident out in the ocean in that boat.  

1336
02:27:46,479 --> 02:27:54,160
It had been some time since anybody had gone 
fishing in this floating wreck. I stuck my head  

1337
02:27:54,160 --> 02:28:02,160
into a cabin. On a table lay U.S. Navy charts for 
the south Long Island coast and New York Harbor.

1338
02:28:03,439 --> 02:28:07,919
"See those charts?" said Lockhart. 
"They're all up-to-date."

1339
02:28:09,359 --> 02:28:11,839
"What about the crew?" I asked.

1340
02:28:12,560 --> 02:28:19,520
"All four crew members were captured. The boat 
was kept under observation by a helicopter from  

1341
02:28:19,520 --> 02:28:25,840
the Cape Cod Air Station. As you know, 
there's easy road access to Jones Beach,  

1342
02:28:26,399 --> 02:28:29,280
so we picked them up as soon 
as the boat was wrecked.  

1343
02:28:30,240 --> 02:28:36,719
They were carrying Russian identification. They 
claim they don't understand a word of English,  

1344
02:28:37,280 --> 02:28:43,679
so we've arranged for an interpreter. Whether 
we get anything out of them is another matter.  

1345
02:28:44,640 --> 02:28:47,920
They've been taken to the Coast 
Guard First District headquarters."

1346
02:28:49,600 --> 02:28:51,760
Lockhart led me down below deck.  

1347
02:28:52,720 --> 02:28:58,000
There were a series of cabins fitted 
with beds with cheap nylon sleeping bags.  

1348
02:28:59,120 --> 02:29:06,000
There were signs of recent occupation. The 
air smelled of stale tobacco. On the floor  

1349
02:29:06,000 --> 02:29:13,439
lay Russian magazines, playing cards, smashed 
plates and cups, and the remains of a meal.

1350
02:29:15,040 --> 02:29:19,359
"According to my calculations, 
there's accommodation down here  

1351
02:29:19,359 --> 02:29:22,960
for fifteen people plus crew," said Lockhart.  

1352
02:29:23,840 --> 02:29:30,240
"This could be the boat that those poor Russian 
boys were in, but I can't prove anything."

1353
02:29:31,680 --> 02:29:36,800
"Five bodies so far. So if 
they had been shipped here  

1354
02:29:36,800 --> 02:29:41,520
on this boat there are potentially 
more fatalities?" I asked.

1355
02:29:42,479 --> 02:29:48,319
"Yes. It's unlikely there would have been any 
survivors from the lifeboat," said Lockhart.

1356
02:29:49,680 --> 02:29:56,480
I accompanied Lockhart up to the bridge. 
Inside, it was full of sophisticated equipment.

1357
02:29:57,840 --> 02:30:00,240
"The boat may look like a wreck,  

1358
02:30:00,240 --> 02:30:05,359
but they've installed the latest satellite 
navigation system," explained Lockhart.

1359
02:30:06,240 --> 02:30:12,000
"Look at this little device. It gives 
you your exact position wherever you are.  

1360
02:30:13,120 --> 02:30:20,640
My theory is the appearance of this boat 
is a deliberate disguise. From a distance,  

1361
02:30:20,640 --> 02:30:27,201
it looks like any other fishing boat. A perfect 
cover for smuggling in illegal immigrants.  

1362
02:30:28,399 --> 02:30:33,040
No ship's log, though, so we have 
no record of the boat's movements.  

1363
02:30:34,240 --> 02:30:38,240
If you come outside, there's 
one last thing to show you."

1364
02:30:39,680 --> 02:30:46,241
Lockhart took me outside. "Look," 
he said. "The lifeboat's missing.  

1365
02:30:46,240 --> 02:30:51,920
But I can't prove yet that the lifeboat 
wrecked on the beach came from this boat."

1366
02:30:53,439 --> 02:31:00,240
"So if you have this boat, does that mean it's 
the end of the smuggling operation?" I asked.

1367
02:31:01,439 --> 02:31:08,240
"We can't tell," he replied. "It wouldn't 
surprise me if they had several boats operating.  

1368
02:31:09,200 --> 02:31:14,080
Also, we have no idea how 
many smuggling operations are  

1369
02:31:14,080 --> 02:31:21,439
active at one time. We're going to double Coast 
Guard patrols off the south Long Island shore."

1370
02:31:23,359 --> 02:31:28,639
Back in Lockhart's car, I showed him the 
document from Romanov's computer file.

1371
02:31:30,000 --> 02:31:34,560
"Take a look at these dates," I 
said. "Are there any connections  

1372
02:31:34,560 --> 02:31:39,600
with incidents reported to the Coast Guard or 
that the Coast Guard has been involved with?"

1373
02:31:41,120 --> 02:31:47,920
After examining the list of dates carefully, 
Lockhart said: "Yes, there's a definite  

1374
02:31:47,920 --> 02:31:55,840
pattern here. Some of these dates match 
up. Where did you get this information?"

1375
02:31:55,840 --> 02:32:02,480
"From the computer files of an Alexei Romanov, 
who was found brutally murdered last week.  

1376
02:32:03,520 --> 02:32:09,041
I'm reasonably sure he was doing his own 
investigation of an immigrant smuggling  

1377
02:32:09,040 --> 02:32:14,880
operation. He must have asked too many 
awkward questions and paid the price."

1378
02:32:16,560 --> 02:32:20,880
Lockhart pointed to the final date 
on the list, which was the next day,  

1379
02:32:21,680 --> 02:32:30,160
Saturday March 16th. "This could indicate another 
delivery of immigrants will arrive tomorrow."

1380
02:32:31,760 --> 02:32:38,880
I told Lockhart about what Edie Tilden had seen 
at the Fire Island - the big smartly dressed  

1381
02:32:38,880 --> 02:32:46,080
guy looking out to sea through binoculars. 
"Of course, it could be nothing," I said,  

1382
02:32:46,800 --> 02:32:52,240
"but I suspect he was checking out Fire 
Island as a possible landing point."

1383
02:32:53,920 --> 02:33:01,040
Lockhart unfolded a map of the Long Island 
beaches. "Let's suppose that a boat is going to be  

1384
02:33:01,040 --> 02:33:10,479
landed on Fire Island. There are lots of beaches 
but very limited road access across the bay. Any  

1385
02:33:10,479 --> 02:33:18,959
vehicle would have to return via Jones Beach from 
this point at the tip of Fire Island, and then  

1386
02:33:18,960 --> 02:33:26,000
there are only three points of access back to Long 
Island. They'd be caught like rats in a trap."

1387
02:33:27,439 --> 02:33:33,839
"Maybe, but you still wouldn't catch whoever's 
in charge of the whole operation," I commented.

1388
02:33:35,280 --> 02:33:42,000
Lockhart thought for a moment, then said, "I'll 
have to contact my superior officer and talk  

1389
02:33:42,000 --> 02:33:50,319
this over. I think the immediate plan of action 
should be a joint Coast Guard and NYPD operation."

1390
02:33:52,080 --> 02:33:58,880
Lockhart dropped me off at Babylon Station. 
I phoned ahead to Stella and arranged to meet  

1391
02:33:58,880 --> 02:34:06,560
her at Cafe Paris on Brighton Beach Avenue. She 
had already set up a meeting with Mrs. Romanov  

1392
02:34:06,560 --> 02:34:15,600
at her home. We had names and addresses of people 
from Alexei Romanov's computer file. To make  

1393
02:34:15,600 --> 02:34:22,480
any progress we would need Mrs. Romanov with us 
because of her status in the Russian community.

1394
02:34:24,160 --> 02:34:31,760
Stella was looking more bright and cheerful. The 
fact that Jose was at last on the road to recovery  

1395
02:34:31,760 --> 02:34:39,760
must have been a huge relief. Just as we were 
about to leave the restaurant to see Mrs. Romanov,  

1396
02:34:39,760 --> 02:34:43,840
there was a call from Kamenev. 
He'd been doing some research  

1397
02:34:44,640 --> 02:34:53,281
and had discovered a company called 'Mossolov 
Import and Export.' In my experience, a business  

1398
02:34:53,280 --> 02:35:01,280
which describes its function as 'import and 
export' could mean anything. It was a conveniently  

1399
02:35:01,280 --> 02:35:08,639
vague term that could apply to any number of 
activities. Was importing immigrants one of them?

1400
02:35:09,920 --> 02:35:12,480
"I'll tell you another thing," said Kamenev.  

1401
02:35:13,359 --> 02:35:20,880
"I phoned several times but just got an answering 
machine each time. When someone finally answered  

1402
02:35:20,880 --> 02:35:26,800
they just hung up without saying a word 
when I asked to speak to Mossolov."

1403
02:35:28,080 --> 02:35:32,000
"Good work, Victor. Do you 
have an address?" I asked.

1404
02:35:33,439 --> 02:35:41,919
The business was located on Brighton Beach Avenue. 
It would be worth checking out. A guy like Zernov  

1405
02:35:41,920 --> 02:35:50,399
wouldn't act on his own initiative. He wasn't 
paid to think. He would obey the boss's orders,  

1406
02:35:50,399 --> 02:35:58,479
and that boss could be the mysterious Mossolov. 
I passed on the information to Captain Oldenberg  

1407
02:35:59,040 --> 02:36:05,760
and also informed him about my meeting 
with Lockhart. More leads for the NYPD  

1408
02:36:05,760 --> 02:36:14,000
to follow up. Oldenberg promised to put an NYPD 
surveillance unit in place to watch the office.

1409
02:36:15,840 --> 02:36:21,120
At the Romanov house, I described the 
Russian fishing boat and its probable  

1410
02:36:21,120 --> 02:36:28,160
function to Mrs. Romanov. She listened 
carefully, obviously upset by what she heard.  

1411
02:36:29,280 --> 02:36:33,519
She turned away and held a 
handkerchief to her eyes for a moment.  

1412
02:36:34,720 --> 02:36:39,200
Then she turned back to me and 
told me what progress she had made.

1413
02:36:40,720 --> 02:36:47,840
Mrs. Romanov had already made contact with 
one of the people on the list, Boris Tchernov,  

1414
02:36:48,640 --> 02:36:55,680
a young man her husband had helped personally. 
She had made an appointment with Tchernov,  

1415
02:36:55,680 --> 02:36:57,201
who would come to her house.

1416
02:36:58,960 --> 02:37:05,200
Tchernov was in his late twenties. He was 
an immigrant who had been in the U.S.A. for  

1417
02:37:05,200 --> 02:37:11,280
almost twelve months. His English was 
good enough to communicate effectively  

1418
02:37:11,280 --> 02:37:18,479
without the need for an interpreter. He had 
met Alexei Romanov and was sincerely grateful  

1419
02:37:18,479 --> 02:37:23,200
for all the assistance he had received 
from the Immigrant Welfare Society.

1420
02:37:24,720 --> 02:37:29,680
"Mr. Tchernov, does the name 'Mossolov' 
mean anything to you?" I asked.

1421
02:37:30,720 --> 02:37:34,160
He shook his head. "I've never heard of it."

1422
02:37:35,359 --> 02:37:39,280
"What about 'Nick'? 'Nick Zernov'?" I asked.

1423
02:37:40,479 --> 02:37:46,879
I could see an anxious expression as I 
said the name. Tchernov knew all about him.

1424
02:37:48,160 --> 02:37:54,559
"I can tell you all about Zernov. 
Three years ago, I was living in Minsk,  

1425
02:37:55,120 --> 02:38:01,439
back in the old country. It was 
a hard life. There were ten of us  

1426
02:38:01,439 --> 02:38:08,160
living in a little apartment in one of the old 
Soviet buildings on the outskirts of the city.  

1427
02:38:09,280 --> 02:38:16,719
I'd always dreamed of a new life in the U.S.A. 
But it was difficult to emigrate legally.  

1428
02:38:17,760 --> 02:38:25,200
There's a limited number of visas available. I 
heard some gossip around that there were other  

1429
02:38:25,200 --> 02:38:34,319
means of entering the country. What you needed 
was three thousand U.S. dollars. A man called  

1430
02:38:34,319 --> 02:38:41,840
Nick visited regularly, made all the arrangements, 
and promised that jobs would be waiting for us."

1431
02:38:43,439 --> 02:38:51,120
Tchernov continued with more details of the 
operation: "Provided you had the money, no  

1432
02:38:51,120 --> 02:39:00,479
questions were asked. I finally met him. Exactly 
as I had imagined - well-dressed, successful.  

1433
02:39:01,520 --> 02:39:09,680
He told me stories about the U.S.A., the land 
of opportunity where any man could realize his  

1434
02:39:09,680 --> 02:39:18,000
ambition - as long as you had the dollars. 
I worked every hour I could, I borrowed,  

1435
02:39:18,640 --> 02:39:25,920
and, I'm ashamed to say, I stole. 
I didn't care how I got that cash."

1436
02:39:27,520 --> 02:39:36,081
"There was no question of flying us in. We were 
taken to the Baltic Coast, near St. Petersburg,  

1437
02:39:36,640 --> 02:39:45,440
to an isolated fishing port. I couldn't believe 
the boat they put us in. The conditions were  

1438
02:39:45,439 --> 02:39:56,479
awful - disgusting food, cold damp cabins, even 
rats. There must have been twenty of us on board.  

1439
02:39:57,600 --> 02:40:05,840
Crossing the Atlantic, one of the guys became 
seriously sick. He had terrible stomach pains.  

1440
02:40:06,960 --> 02:40:13,920
We begged the captain to radio 
for help, but he refused. The guy  

1441
02:40:13,920 --> 02:40:22,399
died after four days. They wrapped him up in an 
old sheet, tied a lump of concrete to his feet,  

1442
02:40:23,120 --> 02:40:30,880
and dropped him overboard. I don't imagine 
his family ever got a refund from Nick."

1443
02:40:32,479 --> 02:40:40,559
"The Atlantic crossing took about ten days. Most 
of the time it was stormy, we were exhausted  

1444
02:40:40,560 --> 02:40:47,840
and seasick. Finally we were all put into 
a small lifeboat in the middle of the night  

1445
02:40:48,479 --> 02:40:54,319
and dropped off on a deserted beach. 
Nick was waiting there with a truck.  

1446
02:40:55,439 --> 02:41:02,160
We were ordered to get in and lie on the floor 
and were taken to an empty factory building.  

1447
02:41:03,200 --> 02:41:13,200
I remember there was some sort of railroad track 
on the floor. We waited there and eventually we  

1448
02:41:13,200 --> 02:41:21,519
were taken in small groups to various addresses 
in the Brighton Beach and Coney Island area."

1449
02:41:23,359 --> 02:41:30,319
"Once we'd arrived, we learned 
the true reality of our situation.  

1450
02:41:30,319 --> 02:41:37,519
We were in the U.S.A. without entry visas 
and had none of the standard documentation.  

1451
02:41:38,800 --> 02:41:44,400
In effect, we were non-persons 
and totally in Nick's power.  

1452
02:41:45,600 --> 02:41:54,080
If I was discovered by the authorities, I could be 
sent straight back to Belarus. He could exploit us  

1453
02:41:54,080 --> 02:42:01,519
any way he liked. We were given really 
miserable jobs in kitchens or workshops,  

1454
02:42:02,319 --> 02:42:09,519
working twelve hours a day or more for very 
little money - and me with a good education.  

1455
02:42:10,720 --> 02:42:18,241
My life was being dominated by him. I escaped 
but found myself living on the streets."

1456
02:42:19,680 --> 02:42:28,160
"I was confused and didn't know how I would cope. 
Then, I contacted the Immigrant Welfare Society.  

1457
02:42:29,279 --> 02:42:40,160
Mr. Romanov was very kind to me and gave me money 
for food and rent. Such a good man. He was helping  

1458
02:42:40,160 --> 02:42:45,920
me with my application for a Green Card 
so I could become a legal resident.  

1459
02:42:47,040 --> 02:42:54,080
I was so shocked when I heard that he'd been 
murdered. Who could have done such a thing?"

1460
02:42:55,680 --> 02:42:58,480
Tchernov had come to the end of his story.  

1461
02:42:59,600 --> 02:43:04,161
I took out Zernov's photograph which 
we had received from Oldenberg.

1462
02:43:05,439 --> 02:43:11,839
"This picture was taken some time ago. Does 
this guy look anything like Nick?" I asked.

1463
02:43:13,200 --> 02:43:16,639
Boris examined the picture 
closely and handed it back.

1464
02:43:17,840 --> 02:43:23,440
"He's put on weight and lost 
some hair, but that's him."
 
 

1465
02:43:26,960 --> 02:43:28,080
CHAPTER THIRTEEN

1466
02:43:28,960 --> 02:43:30,960
A message from Mossolov

1467
02:43:33,040 --> 02:43:40,399
It was almost six o'clock by the time we got back 
to East 43rd Street. The light on the answering  

1468
02:43:40,399 --> 02:43:50,160
machine was flashing. Stella pressed the playback 
button. A brief but threatening anonymous message:

1469
02:43:50,160 --> 02:43:56,000
"If you know what's good for your 
health, keep out of our business."

1470
02:43:57,680 --> 02:44:04,960
Someone was trying to warn us off and was 
prepared to use violence. But I wasn't  

1471
02:44:04,960 --> 02:44:12,720
intending to lose any sleep over it. We had done 
enough for one day and I told Stella to go home.  

1472
02:44:14,000 --> 02:44:20,479
I stayed on at the office for a while, sorting 
through some old case papers and filing them away.  

1473
02:44:21,920 --> 02:44:29,040
The phone rang. I grabbed it and said: 
"Marley speaking." But there was just  

1474
02:44:29,040 --> 02:44:36,479
silence. Exactly the same thing happened 
twice again, at fifteen-minute intervals.  

1475
02:44:37,600 --> 02:44:45,840
Whoever was at the other end wasn't talkative. 
I was starting to get suspicious. We have one of  

1476
02:44:45,840 --> 02:44:53,200
those phones that displays the caller's number. I 
tried calling the number, but there was no answer.  

1477
02:44:54,560 --> 02:44:59,840
Maybe someone was keeping track of where I was.

1478
02:44:59,840 --> 02:45:05,680
I put a call through to the Coast Guard 
to see if Lockhart had anything to report  

1479
02:45:05,680 --> 02:45:13,120
from their patrols off southern Long Island. 
Nothing as yet. It had been a long day,  

1480
02:45:13,760 --> 02:45:20,720
and the ideal way to finish it off was an 
appointment with a cold beer at McFadden's Bar.

1481
02:45:22,399 --> 02:45:26,639
Outside, East 43rd Street 
was practically deserted.  

1482
02:45:27,760 --> 02:45:34,320
Was it my imagination or was there someone 
watching me in the shadows of a service entrance  

1483
02:45:34,319 --> 02:45:43,679
across the street? I went over to investigate. 
Nobody there. Either my eyes were playing tricks  

1484
02:45:43,680 --> 02:45:50,160
on me or I was turning into a nervous 
wreck. Definitely time for that beer.  

1485
02:45:51,359 --> 02:45:56,719
I would feel more comfortable where there 
was noise, bright lights and company.

1486
02:45:58,240 --> 02:46:05,359
I ordered a large beer and stayed by the bar for a 
while, chatting with some of the regular guys from  

1487
02:46:05,359 --> 02:46:14,880
the Daily News. The tiredness was beginning to hit 
me. Time to go home. But I'd forgotten something.  

1488
02:46:15,680 --> 02:46:21,760
I patted my pockets and realized I'd left 
the keys to my apartment in the office.

1489
02:46:23,520 --> 02:46:29,600
Returning along East 43rd Street, I 
suddenly became aware of a large black  

1490
02:46:29,600 --> 02:46:37,840
limo following me very slowly. I turned around and 
started walking rapidly in the other direction.  

1491
02:46:39,279 --> 02:46:46,800
As I was passing the car, it stopped and a 
door suddenly swung open, blocking my path.  

1492
02:46:47,920 --> 02:46:54,960
I stepped aside to avoid the door, but a large, 
heavily built guy was already out of the car,  

1493
02:46:55,600 --> 02:47:03,201
standing directly in front of me. I immediately 
recognized the bushy eyebrows and broken nose:  

1494
02:47:04,080 --> 02:47:12,880
Nick Zernov. He was easily six inches taller 
than me. The street was completely deserted.  

1495
02:47:13,840 --> 02:47:20,800
If I tried to run, I knew Zernov, being younger 
and in better shape, would easily catch me.  

1496
02:47:21,920 --> 02:47:25,120
The only sensible thing to do was to talk.

1497
02:47:26,640 --> 02:47:30,241
"Good evening. Lost your 
way or something?" I asked.

1498
02:47:31,520 --> 02:47:37,520
Zernov's response was to lift me up 
effortlessly by my coat. His forehead  

1499
02:47:37,520 --> 02:47:44,241
was now level with my nose. That's what I 
call a serious invasion of personal space.  

1500
02:47:45,439 --> 02:47:49,120
I didn't like the idea of 
my nose being broken either.

1501
02:47:50,560 --> 02:48:00,880
"Marley, I have a message from Mossolov," said 
Zernov. "Stop asking questions. Don't stick your  

1502
02:48:00,880 --> 02:48:09,359
big nose in our business! Mossolov knows you've 
been watching us and wants you to call your people  

1503
02:48:09,359 --> 02:48:15,839
off. Otherwise, I'll have to break 
your legs. Is that clear, Marley?"

1504
02:48:17,200 --> 02:48:22,319
"Couldn't be clearer," I replied. 
"Message received and understood."

1505
02:48:23,520 --> 02:48:29,840
Zernov got back inside the car 
which sped off towards Park Avenue.

1506
02:48:29,840 --> 02:48:36,560
I'd learned two things from the meeting. First, 
that Zernov was definitely working for Mossolov.  

1507
02:48:37,600 --> 02:48:44,640
Second, Mossolov thought I had been watching them. 
They hadn't connected the surveillance operation  

1508
02:48:44,640 --> 02:48:52,880
with the NYPD. This was a possible advantage. If 
they didn't think that the police were involved,  

1509
02:48:52,880 --> 02:49:00,400
they might still go ahead with another immigrant 
smuggling operation. I'd have to contact Oldenberg  

1510
02:49:00,399 --> 02:49:07,839
to tell him to make the police operation less 
obvious. Then they'd assume they'd scared me off.

1511
02:49:09,520 --> 02:49:13,041
I went back to the office 
and called Captain Oldenberg.  

1512
02:49:14,000 --> 02:49:19,520
Fortunately he was still at his desk. 
I explained what had just happened.

1513
02:49:20,720 --> 02:49:23,920
"Do you have anything new on Zernov?" I asked.

1514
02:49:24,800 --> 02:49:27,840
"We have some good photos," Oldenberg said.  

1515
02:49:28,880 --> 02:49:35,600
"Zernov was twice seen entering the Mossolov 
Import Export office on Brighton Beach Avenue.  

1516
02:49:36,160 --> 02:49:42,639
But we haven't had a sighting of the boss of 
the organization. Zernov's been seen with two  

1517
02:49:42,640 --> 02:49:48,400
men and a woman on a couple of occasions. 
I'll email some pictures through to you."

1518
02:49:50,080 --> 02:49:54,960
One more call before I could go 
home. This time to Joe Blaney.

1519
02:49:56,080 --> 02:50:03,600
"Joe, I've had a serious threat made against 
me. I need protection. You'll need to be armed.  

1520
02:50:04,640 --> 02:50:10,960
And another thing, will you rent a car? 
Anything that's powerful but looks anonymous.  

1521
02:50:11,840 --> 02:50:13,040
Could you start this evening?"

1522
02:50:13,920 --> 02:50:18,480
"Sure, boss. I'm not doing anything 
else at the moment," Joe replied.

1523
02:50:19,600 --> 02:50:25,760
"OK, then. Pack a suitcase and come 
to my apartment at 9:00 PM," I said.

1524
02:50:27,359 --> 02:50:33,040
On the subway home, I immediately 
fell fast asleep but knew,  

1525
02:50:33,040 --> 02:50:39,120
as always, I'd wake up just before the 
train arrived at Main Street, Queens.  

1526
02:50:40,000 --> 02:50:47,279
It's a technique I've developed over long years 
of commuting. On Main Street, I bought a bottle  

1527
02:50:47,279 --> 02:50:53,599
of chilled white wine at the local liquor 
store and got myself a Korean take-out meal.  

1528
02:50:54,720 --> 02:50:59,680
It was my intention finally to have 
the quiet evening I'd promised myself.

1529
02:51:01,200 --> 02:51:07,760
When Joe arrived I knew I would sleep 
more soundly. It's reassuring to have an  

